<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deputy Yugoslav Minister Denied Access into Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides Tuesday confirmed reports that a deputy Yugoslav
minister was denied access into Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Kasoulides said the decision is part of
the policy of the Cypriot government to align with European Union
(EU) measures against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus has opted to go along the path leading to
Europe. Cyprus is holding membership talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also said the entry denial decision does
not constitute a hostile action. He did not mention the name of
the deputy Yugoslav minister.
</P>
<P>
He said the bilateral relations between Cyprus and Yugoslavia
remain friendly and "we believe Yugoslavia understands the
difficulties we are facing."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has decided to align itself as far as
possible with the EU sanctions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions include a ban on the entry of some 300 Yugoslav
politicians, military officials, journalists and members of
President Slobodan Milosevic's family into EU member states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
