<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Integration Must Be Balanced: Ugandan President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Regional integration must be
balanced, Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni said at the closing
ceremony of the fourth summit of the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) in Kenyan capital Nairobi Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
By emphasizing balanced integration, Museveni noted the
balanced investment and the free movement of capital and labor are
as important as that of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Without investment, the rich hydro, mineral, tourism resources
in the sub-region couldn't be tapped, he said.
</P>
<P>
Regional integration is not easy to achieve, the president
said, hinting that if not properly managed, it might ignite
business wars.
</P>
<P>
However, there is no opportunity of development without
integration because the individual markets in the sub-region are
too small and fragmented to compete in the world trade.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, the newly-elected chairman of
 COMESA, also noted at the summit that globalization has
threatened to marginalize the sub-region, causing capital outflow
and provoking protectionism.
</P>
<P>
Regional integration is both essential and crucial to offset
the impact of the globalization, he said, urging the COMESA
members to buy goods and services from within the region and to
develop industry.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA is counting down toward the attainment of a
free-trade area by October 31, 2000. And the trade bloc is also
aiming to create a free investment area as soon as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
