<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan-Zambian Ties Normal: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Ambassador to Zambia Manuel
Augusto said Tuesday that his country enjoys normal relations with
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a rally to mark 36th anniversary of African
Freedom Day here, he told the press that although the two
countries are having a tense time at the moment, the Angolan
people are grateful to Zambia for what it did for the liberation
of Angola.
</P>
<P>
Augusto said that once peace is achieved in Angola it will be
of advantage to the Zambian people and their government because
the economy of the country will be boosted.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that the talks held in Mbabane, Swaziland,
between Zambia and Angola were meant to be a first step to find
ways of resolving the problems.
</P>
<P>
The talks went on as scheduled and the presidents of the two
countries will eventually meet to end the standoff.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the Angolan government would like the
Zambian government to fire its ministers, who have been charged by
Angola with supplying arms to the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), he said Angola can't interfere in
the decision of the Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year Angola repeatedly accused Zambia of supplying
arms to UNITA rebels while Zambia strongly denied the charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
