<HEADLINE> Germany Reports Billions Losses in Alpine Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Losses up to 2.1 billion marks (1.1
billion U.S. dollars) have been caused by days of floods that hit
Germany's southern regions near Alpine Mountains, officials said
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the southern state of Bavaria, regions of about 120 square
kilometers were over-flooded, said Environment State Secretary
Christa Stewens, adding that 25,000 properties were damaged by the
floods.
</P>
<P>
At least 4 people were killed in Bavaria by floods, and other
two, who were missing 3 days ago, were feared dead.
</P>
<P>
The Bavarian state government has deployed thousands of workers
to cope with the floods. But cities near the river of Donau and
the lake of Bodensee were still in a state of emergency until
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Konstanz, the water gauge remained 5.65 meter on
Tuesday, 2 meters over normal level. If the water rises over 6
meter, the old city would be submerged.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of workers were busy blocking the dam breaks to defend
the tiny city of Neustadt on Tuesday. The city with 12,000
residents is in "top crisis", said local authorities.
</P>
<P>
Although fewer clouds over the region were expected in coming
days, experts warned against threats from melting mountain snow.
People in the region may have to live with floods for weeks, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The German Weather Service on Tuesday forecast an early Summer
in Alpine region. A much warmer weather will prevail in the
mountainous region, parts of which are covered by meters-deep
snow.
</P>
<P>
Because large amount of snow will melt in the mountains, there
is a danger that further floods hit the Alpine region following
weeks, said Gerhard Benz, geologist with Muenchner Rueck, world's
largest reassurance company.  
</P>
</TEXT>
