<HEADLINE> Tanzanian FM Urges African Nations to Unite for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Africa should unite to
develop economy, and fight for debt relief so that it will not be
dropped out in the next century, Tanzanian foreign minister Jakaya
Kikwete said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Russian Cultural Center in Dar es Salaam in an
occasion to mark the African Day, Kikwete told the African
diplomats accredited to Tanzania that the continent needs unity
now than ever before.
</P>
<P>
"We need to speak in one voice, particularly when facing rich
and powerful nations and international financial and economic
entities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete said it is important that African countries, which have
not joined any economic groupings, make a move to join the nearest
one.
</P>
<P>
"Our biggest challenge in the next millenium is to ensure the
realization of the African Economic Community in concrete terms,"
he said. " Our survival depends on it."
</P>
<P>
He appealed to African countries to invest more in education,
science and technology if it wants to ensure development in the
next century.
</P>
<P>
"If we have to make the next century as Africa's we have to
invest more in education and advancement of science and
technology," he said, adding that the continent is not doing
enough at the moment.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister cited Japan and the Republic of Korea
which committed themselves to education and training as countries
that have made great strides in human development and economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete further spoke of the exigency of African countries
jointly fighting to ensure the removal of debt burden, saying that
if the step is not taken, the continent will lose another chance
to develop.
</P>
<P>
Africa's debt has been growing at a rate of more than 23
percent annually, which is higher than the growth rate of gross
domestic product (GDP) and exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
"By 1999 the debt and debt servicing rose to 203.9 dollars per
person while the income is barely 221.4 dollars per capita," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister lauded the founding fathers of African countries
for their commitment and dedication to forming the Organization of
African Unity on May 25, 1963.
</P>
<P>
But he said it is imperative to restructure the organization
and amend its charter.
</P>
<P>
The objective, he said, is to "have a leaner and more efficient
 organization that will advance both political and economic
interests of Africa."
</P>
<P>
He said the amendment task should be completed before the
continent enters the next millenium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
