<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Close In Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- A strong opening on Wall Street
halted the slide in Europe in late trade Tuesday, but it wasn't
enough to prevent all bourses finishing in the red.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 ended the day 72.8 points lower at 6249.3,
having touched a mid-afternoon session floor of 6184.8.
Provisional volume for the whole market was 1bn shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Banks and insurers were the heaviest hit sectors, just a day
after a selective rally boosted much of the sector following
confirmation that Alliance &AMP; Leicester and Bank of Ireland are in
talks. Alliance stock, which surged Monday, fell 2 percent at the
close.
</P>
<P>
Others in the sector to suffer included mortgage lender
Halifax, down 2.8 percent, and investment bank Schroders, which
slumped almost 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
German's Xetra DAX closed at 5165.72, down 88.05 from Friday's
close. The market was closed for a religious holiday on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The big loser was Deutsche Telekom, whose merger with Telecom
Italia has been blocked by Olivertti's takeover of the Italian
company.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the Cac 40 index of leading shares pared its losses
after Wall Street's opening, ending down 24.35 points at 4373.78,
having earlier hit a low of 4314.46.
</P>
<P>
Telecoms stocks were the main focus of trading, with dealers
worried that the fall-out from Olivetti's takeover of Telecom
Italia could hurt French companies.
</P>
<P>
France Telecom was the main loser, with its shares falling 1.40
euros, or 2 percent, to 72.50, and accounting for 10 percent of
the index's overall decline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
