<HEADLINE> Cyprus' EU Access Course Faces New Obstacles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 25 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government said Tuesday
that it will not to respond immediately to some obstacles that
have arisen in its European Union (EU) accession process.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that Britain, France and Germany have
attempted to raise obstacles to Cyprus' EU course because of the
pro-Yugoslav position the Cyprus' Parliament has adopted.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, Slovenia, Hungary, Poland, Estonia and the Czech
Republic started substantive accession negotiations with the EU in
November 1998.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the three countries will be willing to close
the chapter of EU accession negotiations, one of 31, for the other
five candidate countries but keep it open for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"At the stage, the government does not consider it appropriate
to comment in public on this issue," Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will respond if the matter, being
watched closely, moves on for discussion at the EU institutions.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides also noted that there were difficulties on other
issues in the past, but they were coped with.
</P>
<P>
Parliament Speaker Spyros Kyprianou described the attempts of
Britain, France and Germany as a kind of pressure.
</P>
<P>
A parliament resolution, adopted in early April, unanimously
condemned North Atlantic Treaty Organization's bombing against
Yugoslavia and stressed that its territorial integrity and
sovereignty should be respected.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus Parliament also called on the international
community to exert pressure to end the bombing and seek a
political settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
