<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, May 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Israel's new government led by Ehud Barak will
seek comprehensive peace with Syria and Lebanon, former Israeli
Prime Minister Shimon Peres said.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who was elected Israel's new prime minister on May 17,
"will give top priority to working out a full peace settlement
with Syria and Lebanon," Peres said in an interview at his Tel
Aviv bureau with Kuwaiti Arabic daily Al-Rai Al-A'm published here
Tuesday. (BC-Israel-Arabs-Peace)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The ground-breaking ceremony for Khodashahr (God's
city), the first high-tech city to be built in Iran's central
desert, was held in Ardestan region of Isfahan province, the
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With investments from overseas Iranians, the city is to be
built on the edge of the country's central acid desert Dasht-e
Kavir with an area of 3,600 square kilometers. (BC-Iran-Desert-City)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In a bid to form a broad-based coalition
government, the negotiating team appointed by Israel's Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak Tuesday met with right-wing Likud Party
officials in the northern city of Herzliya.
</P>
<P>
The Likud representatives did not discuss with Barak's team
about the possibility of their joining of the new government at
the meeting, Israel Radio reported. But they only asked questions
on Barak's guidelines concerning political, security and economic
issues. (BC-Israel-Coalition Talks)
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- U.S. and British warplanes on Tuesday bombed some
civilian facilities in northern Iraq and inflicted damage on some
civilian buildings, an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman said that at 11:34 local time (0734 GMT),
11 formations of enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace
violated northern Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Neineva and Erbil
provinces.(BC-Iraq-US Attack)
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides Tuesday
confirmed reports that a deputy Yugoslav minister was denied
access into Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Kasoulides said the decision is part of
the policy of the Cypriot government to align with European Union
(EU) measures against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus has opted to go along the path leading to
Europe. Cyprus is holding membership talks with the
EU. (BC-Cyprus-Yugoslavia)


25/05/99 19:54 GMT

