<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: COMESA on Fast Track of Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 25 (Xinhua) -- The heads of state and government
and representatives from the 21 member states of the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) have voiced their
determination and commitment to the realization of the COMESA free
trade area by next year.
</P>
<P>
With the theme of "Countdown to the COMESA free trade area,"
the fourth COMESA summit ended in Nairobi Tuesday, calling on all
member states to adhere to the provisions set in the COMESA Treaty
for zero tariff and to eliminate non-tariff barriers and other
obstacles to trade by October 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
As globalization is enhancing stiff competition toward the 21st
century, African countries are finding it increasingly difficult
to compete in the world market. The globalization has threatened
to marginalize Africa as the current trade volume of some 23
billion U.S. dollars in the COMESA only accounted for less than
0.42 percent of the world total of 5,583 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA leaders agreed that the only solution lies in the
formation of regional economic blocs and they attached great
importance to the integration into the global economic
architecture.
</P>
<P>
In a final communique issued by the summit, the leaders
recalled the decision of declaring the region as a common
investment area for balanced and sustainable development in the
region.
</P>
<P>
They also encouraged the member states, particularly those with
growing cross-border trade, investment and tourism, to introduce
limited currency convertibility between themselves in a bid to
reduce transaction costs, facilitate the flow of trade and
investment, and promote the exchange of local currencies among
member states.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the summit endorsed the
establishment of a special free trade area committee comprising
Kenya, Mauritius, Zambia, Uganda, Egypt, Zimbabwe, Malawi and the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to assist in the preparatory
activities culminating in the launching of the free trade area
next October.
</P>
<P>
The leaders have also decided to form a co-ordinating body of
experts from central banks and ministries of finance to oversee
the implementation of policy measures on economic policy
harmonization toward the eventual goal of a monetary union by
2025.
</P>
<P>
For promoting cross-border trade within the region, the leaders
decided that all member states should adopt the harmonized
commodity description and coding system for customs and
statistics, and agreed to the need of setting up a guarantee
facility for covering political risks in intra- COMESA and
international trade.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized that peace, unity and stability are the keys to
the economic growth in the region. "Peace is of paramount
importance," Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, the newly-elected
COMESA chairman, pointed out. " Without peace, there would be
nothing but poverty."
</P>
<P>
The leaders also appealed to those member states involved in
regional or civil conflicts to cease fire immediately for the sake
of trade growth and regional economic integration as well as the
improvement of the well-being of the people in the region.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment in 1994, the COMESA has made
commendable progress toward the attainment of the goals of a free
trade area by October next year and a common external tariffs by
2004, said Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, the outgoing
COMESA Chairman.
</P>
<P>
As of February 1, 1999, Chiluba said, 14 out of the 21 member
states had reduced their tariffs by between 60 percent and 90
percent. Non-tariff barriers like licenses, import quotas and
foreign exchange restrictions have been removed in most of COMESA
members.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the regional body has pursued the goal of creating a
common market where goods, services, labor and capital can move
freely across the borders of its member states, Chiluba told the
summit.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA covers an area of some 12.88 million square
kilometers with a population of 380 million. However its current
gross domestic product (GDP) is only 165 billion dollars, just as
much as that of Belgium or the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Endowed with rich natural resource and a big market, the COMESA
would be like a magnet for potential investors within and outside
the region.
</P>
<P>
As Kenyan President Moi said at the opening ceremony of the
summit that African countries must be united in pursuing issue of
common concern. " Together under the COMESA umbrella, we must
work for freedom in trade that will enable us to participate
effectively in and gain from the global economy."
</P>
<P>
Presidents from Zimbabwe, Uganda, Namibia, Tanzania, Sudan,
Malawi, Rwanda, the DRC, Burundi and Djibouti, and ministers from
other COMESA countries, also attended the two-day summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
