<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Launch 39 Million U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia plans to launch in
July this year a national livestock development capacity building
project at a cost of 39 million U.S. dollars, the country's
agriculture ministry announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Project coordinator Hassen Ali was quoted by the Ethiopian News
Agency as saying that 84 percent of the said sum is secured from
the African Development Bank while the federal and state
governments are to cover the balance.
</P>
<P>
Hassen said the five-year project is aimed at bolstering the
country's food security program by way of improved animal
productivity and helping farmers augment their income through the
optimum exploitation of livestock products.
</P>
<P>
He said activities to be carried out by the project include
building the national livestock breeding capacity, improving
veterinary services and distributing hybrid species to farmers.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to produce 288,000 tons of milk, 43,400
tons of beef and mutton as well as 511,000 tons of fodder products
annually, according to the coordinator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
