<HEADLINE> U.S.-British Warplanes Bomb Iraqi Civilian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British warplanes on
Tuesday bombed some civilian facilities in northern Iraq and
inflicted damage on some civilian buildings, an Iraqi military
spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed spokesman said that at 11:34 local time (0734 GMT),
11 formations of enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace
violated northern Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Neineva and Erbil
provinces.
</P>
<P>
The enemy formations attacked civilian facilities including
some civilian buildings in the northern Iraqi city of Mosul, said
the spokesman. He did not mention whether casualties were caused.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back
and forced the enemy planes to flee at 14:45 local time (1045 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Enemy warplanes also violated southern Iraqi airspace at 11:00
local time (0700 GMT) when 11 formations coming from Saudi and
Kuwaiti bases flew over Basra, Thi-Qar, Muthana and Qadisiya
provinces, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched four-night airstrikes
against Iraq last December, their warplanes have been regularly
attacking Iraqi military and civilian targets, causing severe
civilian casualties and property damage.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed no-fly zones in Iraq
following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from
"Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared that it does not recognize these restricted
zones and vowed to continue confronting any allied plane violating
its airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
