<HEADLINE> Stepashin Tables Russian Cabinet's Objectives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin said Tuesday that his cabinet would strive to solve
urgent social issues and increase industrial and agricultural
output as its priority objectives.
</P>
<P>
Delays in payment of pensions, wages and child benefits have to
be resolved, Stepashin said in an interview televised from his
Moscow-bound airplane from Sochi, where he met President Boris
Yeltsin on the formation of the government.
</P>
<P>
Increasing the output of manufacturing industries and
agriculture is another objective, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We should at last break the vicious circle of taxes strangling
the Russian producer," he said.
</P>
<P>
Long-term programs of economic development have to be drafted,
Stepashin said. These issues will be handled by his first deputy,
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov, he said.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that the presidential headquarters and the cabinet
are acting as one team, brushing away allegations that "somebody
is pressuring somebody else in making appointments."
</P>
<P>
"We found an optimal procedure in which we discussed for a week
several candidates for every cabinet position," Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
"I discussed them with Presidential Chief of Staff Alexander
Voloshin and First Deputy Prime Minister Nikolai Aksyonenko, and
then we submitted the proposals to the president."
</P>
<P>
"We succeeded within a week to agree on the appointments to 80
percent of the posts. This is a good result," Stepashin said.
</P>
