<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO to Launch Negotiations on Tobacco Control Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Assembly, the
governing body of the World Health Organization (WHO) has
unanimously decided to open the negotiation process on the
Framework Convention on tobacco Control (FCTC).
</P>
<P>
FCTC is a new legal instrument that will address issues as
diverse as tobacco advertizing and promoting, agricultural
diversification, smuggling, taxes and subsidies.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in its 50-year history that WHO is
exercising its constitutional mandate to negotiate a convention,
said the United Nations agency in a press release here Tuesday.
When ready, the FCTC will be the world's first global tobacco
control treaty.
</P>
<P>
A FCTC working group will soon begin work on proposed draft
elements of the FCTC, thereby paving the road for formal
negotiations to commence in about one year's time. WHO and its
members plan to have the convention process completed by 2003,
after which it will be open for ratification.
</P>
<P>
The resolution on the tobacco control treaty is one of the
major resolutions adopted at the 52nd World Health Assembly, which
met from May 17 to 25 in Geneva.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
