<HEADLINE> Consumer Confidence Remains Strong In May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, May 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer confidence rose
in May for the seventh consecutive month, the Conference Board,
a prominent research group, reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Confidence Index, a key indicator of future
economic activity, rose about one-half point to 135.8 in May
from a revised 135.5 in April, the Board said.
</P>
<P>
"Neither the crisis in Kosovo nor recent price surges at the
gas pump have cooled consumer optimism," said Lynn Franco,
Associate Director of the Board. "Low inflation and a strong job
market are providing a durable foundation for historically-high
levels of consumer confidence."
</P>
<P>
The strong consumer confidence came despite recent reports
that the April consumer price index rose 0.7 percent, the
biggest jump in nearly nine years that prompted the Federal
reserve to lean to monetary tightening.
</P>
<P>
Some 44 percent Americans said current business conditions
are "good", up from 43 percent last month, the Conference Board
said in the report. Only 8.4 percent called business activity
"bad," down from 9.1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed a modest improvement in the outlook
for the next six months. Only 5.5 percent looked for business
conditions to worsen in the next six months, down from 6.2
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
Consumer confidence is an important economic indicator in
the United States because consumer spending accounts for about
two-thirds of the nationa's overall economic activity. The
Consumer Confidence survey is based on representative sample of
5,000 U.S. households.  
</P>
</TEXT>
