<HEADLINE> Barak's Team Meets Likud Officials Over Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 25 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to form a broad-based
coalition government, the negotiating team appointed by Israel's
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak Tuesday met with right-wing Likud
Party officials in the northern city of Herzliya.
</P>
<P>
The Likud representatives did not discuss with Barak's team
about the possibility of their joining the new government at the
meeting, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
But they only asked questions on Barak's guidelines concerning
political, security and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
The radio said that the Likud representatives will present
what they heard to the party's central committee. And senior Likud
officials are expected to meet on Thursday to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Barak, leader of the left-wing One Israel coalition, won a
landslide victory over outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
in the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
He reportedly wants to form a broad-based coalition government
with the support of more than 90 Knesset (parliament) members.
</P>
<P>
Likud, which won 19 seats in the 120-seat Knesset, is still
split over whether to join the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Some Likud officials said joining the coalition would give the
party a chance to have an impact in the final-status talks with
the Palestinians, while others insisted that the party could more
easily expedite a recovery program in the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Barak has 45 days to form a government and his team is
expected to meet with Likud representatives again next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
