<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 100 Die in Nigerian Ethnic Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, May 25 (Xinhua) -- The death toll of the ethnic clashes
in Nigeria's northern town of Kafanchan have surpassed 100.
</P>
<P>
The clashes broke out on Saturday between the Moslem
Hausa-Fulani aristocracy and the minority communities subject to
its rule. Nigerian government has sent armed police and soldiers
to the troubled region, a government official told Xinhua on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the secretary to the State Government, Charles
Bonat said the government had agreed in principle to create a new
chiefdom in the area, and communicated the decision to the
indigenes.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds were killed when fighting flared at Kafanchan in 1987
as Christians from minority ethnic groups clashed with the Moslem
Hausa-Fulani they accused of trying to dominate them.
</P>
<P>
The dominance of the emirates was established across most of
northern Nigeria two centuries ago during a jihad war waged by
cleric Uthman Dan Fodio on inhabitants who mostly practised
traditional African religions.
</P>
<P>
Nigerians from other parts of the West African country of at
least 108 million often accuse the Hausa-Fulani of manipulating
both military and civilian rulers -- mostly northerners -- since
independence from Britain in 1960. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
