<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: U.S. Administration Will Continue Engagement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
Tuesday that his administration will continue the policy of
engagement with China.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly believe that our continuing engagement with China
has produced benefits for our national security," Clinton said in
a speech in Edinburg Town, Texas State.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks after a U.S. congressional report
which asserted China obtained nuclear secrets through "espionage"
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I want to assure you and all the American people that I will
work very hard with the Congress to protect our national security,
to implement the recommendations, and to continue our policy of
engagement, because both of them are in the national interest,"
said Clinton, who was in south Texas State attending a White House
conference on developing rural and urban areas.
</P>
<P>
The 872-page report by a House special committee headed by
Republican lawmaker Chris Cox claimed that China got secret
information on seven nuclear warheads and the neutron bomb in "two
decades of espionage" at U.S. nuclear weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said
Cox's report was merely a fallacy dreamed up by a few people in
the United States with ulterior motives and in essence an attempt
to stir up anti-China feelings and divert people's attention.
</P>
<P>
Some Americans are sticking to the Cold War thinking and are
making a great effort to dream up stories about China's spying on
U.S. nuclear technology, Zhu said at a regular press conference.
"Their despicable attempt is doomed to fail," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
