<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Home PC Penetration in U.S. Climbing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 25 (Xinhua) -- A just-released study from a
market research firm found that more than half of U.S. households
now had at least one personal computer installed.
</P>
<P>
Home PC penetration in the United States has been climbing
sharply the last few years, reaching 50.3 percent earlier this
year, according to the study by La Jolla, California-based ZD
Market Intelligence. This is an increase of 6.4 million households
from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The study, based on more than 10,000 interviews, also found
that households with higher income represent higher percentage in
PC homes. Nearly 40 percent of all U.S. households have annual
income under 30,000 U.S. dollars, but they represent only 23
percent households with a PC. In contrast, households with annual
income 75,000 dollars or more are the minority, accounting for
only 19 percent of al U.S. households, but this smaller group
makes up 27 percent of PC homes.
</P>
<P>
According to the research firm's study last year, of the 102
million U.S. households, 45.6 million, or 44.8 percent, had at
least one PC as of early 1998. The fat part of the PC homes is in
those with middle and upper-middle incomes.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates predicted last year that 65
percent of U.S. households will have at least one PC by the end of
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
