<HEADLINE> EU Welcomes Coca-Cola's Decision to Drop Acquisition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 25 (Xinhua) -- European Commission expressed
satisfaction Tuesday with the Coca-Cola Company's recent decision
to drop its plans to acquire the soft drinks business of Cadbury
Schweppes plc in continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
Karel Van Miert, the European Commissioner responsible for
competition policy, said in a statement that he is pleased with
the cooperation between the European Union (EU) executive body and
EU member states' competition authorities throughout the
investigation of the Coca-Cola acquisition case. "The companies
decision to drop their initial plans is judicious," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Van Miert had earlier this month warned against the
possible anti-competitive effects of the purchase and had
requested the companies to notify the acquisition to the European
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola and Schweppes announced Monday a radical
restructuring of their purchase agreement. The original
agreement, signed last December, provided for Coca-Cola to acquire
all of Schweppes' soft drinks business worldwide, with the
exception of US, France and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Now, the two companies have excluded from their deal all EU
member states with the exception of Britain, Ireland and Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
