<HEADLINE> Germany, U.S. Talk Stress NATO "Unity" on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and visiting German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer Tuesday stressed the "unity" of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization on Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference, Albright and Fischer said
they "see eye-to-eye" on a great deal of issues on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"I think that we really have spent a lot of time talking about
the unity of the alliance, our determination to follow through on
the air campaign and working towards, as I said, preparing for
success," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
Germany has voiced strong opposition to any consideration of
sending NATO combat troops into the Kosovo conflict, now in its
third month, threatening to veto such a move. But Britain strongly
support a ground invasion.
</P>
<P>
As the air campaign against Yugoslavia enters its third month,
sharp splits emerge among the alliance members.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said nothing at the news conference about Germany's
opposition to employing ground troops against the Serbs - an
option that Albright said was still on the table.
</P>
<P>
Both the foreign ministers agreed that there should be a role
for the United Nations and the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"We also do agree that...that there should be a Security
Council resolution. The question is about the timing of it," she
added.
</P>
<P>
On the questions of an ground invasion, Albright reaffirmed
that the United States has not taken options off the table.
</P>
<P>
"But we are very focused now on the air campaign, on having
the expanded K-FOR (Kosovo Implementation Force) be able to
operate effectively and make sure that the planning and early
deployment of that is possible, and keep our eye on what we're
doing," Albright added.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said nothing at the news conference about Germany's
opposition to employing ground troops against the Serbs. "I can
tell you that just now, we are working very hard for a political
solution."
</P>
<P>
"On the other side, we have to prepare ourselves for the case
of the success fo the political solution," He added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
