<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Drop 2.3 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories for
durable goods declined by 4.5 billion dollars last month to a
seasonally adjusted 194.4 billion dollars, the Commerce Department
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The sharp drop of 2.3 percent in April is the second decline in
the past three months. It followed a 2.7 percent increase in March
and was the biggest setback since a 3.9 percent fall in February.
</P>
<P>
Since the world financial crisis began in 1997, one of the U.S.
industries suffering the most has been steel, due to a flood of
cheap imports from countries like Japan. But today's report of the
government showed that the worst may be over.
</P>
<P>
Primary metals, the sector which includes steel, saw orders
increase by 1.3 percent last month following a 0.6 percent decline
in March.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the April's 2.3 percent drop in durable goods orders
was led by a sharp 12.4 percent fall in demand in the
transportation sector, which included decreases in all components
including autos and aircraft, the Department said.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the big drop in the transportation, orders would have
risen by 0.9 percent. That compared to a 2 percent increase
excluding transportation in March.
</P>
<P>
In April, orders for industrial machinery also rose by 3.5
percent, the fourth increase in this sector in the past six
months.
</P>
<P>
But orders for electronic and other electrical equipment were
down 0.7 percent last month following a big 4.5 percent March
increase.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of big-ticket durable goods, a good sign of current
demand, were down 0.6 percent in April after having risen 1.9
percent the previous month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
