<HEADLINE> Conference on Africa Water Resources Policy Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from 22 sub-Sahara
African countries gathered here Wednesday for a three-day
conference on water management polices, which aims to chart the
direction in the field for the 21st century and alleviate the
looming water crisis in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Water security will soon rank with military security in the
war room of defense ministries", said Klaus Toepfer, executive
director of United Nations Environment Program (UNEP).
</P>
<P>
"The signs are clear that the world community must elevate the
issue of water to a position of highest priority," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Vice-President George Saitoti officially opened the
conference following the performance of traditional Kenyan dance
in the conference room.
</P>
<P>
The conference will provide a forum for senior policy and
decision makers to share and draw lessons from their experiences
in water management policy and institutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
Participants are expected to develop a network of African water
 resources professionals and define a program of short-term
actions for management and exchange of water resources knowledge.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. research report, the scarcity of water will
be felt by most African countries soon unless effective measures
are taken. Meanwhile, about 80 percent of all diseases, and more
than a third of deaths in developing countries, are caused by
contaminated water.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, the Kenyan government and the UNEP hosted the
conference from May 26 through 28. UNEP is the lead agency for
water resources management in the U.N. system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
