<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges UN to Send Envoy to Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday urged the U.N.
secretary general to send an envoy to the disputed area of Kashmir
to inspect the deteriorating situation there.
</P>
<P>
Referring to India's airstrikes in the India-controlled part of
Kashmir against "infiltrators," a spokesman of the Pakistani
Foreign Office said, "The secretary general should send an envoy
to the region for the preservation of peace and security."
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing here, the spokesman lashed at India's
airstrikes as "brutal repression of the innocent Kashmiris who are
engaged in an indigenous struggle for their right of
self-determination."
</P>
<P>
Conflicts erupts in the Line of Control (LoC) area from time to
time during the past 50 years. But this is the first time in
recent 20 years that a side resorted to air force in that region.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said some bombs have fallen on the Pakistani
side, which is "clearly a violation of the LoC."
</P>
<P>
"We believe such an escalation (of conflicts) is unwarranted
and it should be avoided," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
For the last two weeks, Pakistani and Indian troops have been
exchanging fire across the LoC.
</P>
<P>
"The Indian military action with aircraft and helicopters
against the Kashmiri Mujahideen once again underscores the
urgency of finding a political solution to the Kashmir dispute,"
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We have noted with satisfaction the statement of the U.N.
secretary general calling for such a solution," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also reiterated that Pakistan is committed to the
 Lahore Declaration signed by the prime ministers of the two
countries in February and to the dialogue process with India.
</P>
<P>
"We call upon India to join us in intensifying efforts to
resolve all disputes specially the core dispute of Kashmir."
</P>
<P>
"We also call upon the international community to recognize the
 serious implications in a continued impasse in the Kashmir
dispute on account of the Indian intransigence and to engage
meaningfully with the process of finding a just and final
settlement of the dispute," the spokesman said. 
</P>
