<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai FM Leaves for Visit to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan Wednesday left for Libya in a bid to boost bilateral ties
and enhancing economic and labor cooperation between the two
countries, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the first visit to the Muslim country by a minister
from member countries of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day visit, Surin is scheduled to meet senior
Libyan officials, but whether he would also meet Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi has yet to be confirmed, TNA said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Foreign Ministry reportedly may discuss the
possibility of establishing a Thai embassy in Tripoli, capital of
Libya, in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Libya's handover of two suspects in the bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1998, which led to the
U.N. removal of economic sanctions against the oil-rich North
African country early last month, has prompted Thailand and other
ASEAN countries to resume cooperation with Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
There are now 7,000 Thai workers in Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
