<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released today:
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Stresses Sino-Kyrgyzstan Relations
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Kyrgyzstan Foreign Minister Muratbek
Sansyzbayevich Yimanaliyev today, Premier Zhu Rongji said that
China is willing to tap the potential of cooperation with
Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
Yimanaliyev said that Kyrgyzstan attaches great importance to
relations with China, and that there is no obstacle in the way of
developing relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Japan Urged to Maintain Only Defense Policy
</P>
<P>
A leading official of the Subcommittee of Foreign Affairs of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
said here today that Japan should adhere to its Peace Constitution
and maintain a defense-only policy.
</P>
<P>
The official made the remarks after the Japanese Senate passed
new Japan-U.S. defense cooperation guidelines. Its House of
Representatives had already approved the documents despite of the
opposition of the Japanese people and the Asian people.
</P>
<P>
Senior CPC Official Meets Bolivian Delegation
</P>
<P>
Huang Ju, a member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, met with a delegation from
Bolivia's Leftist Revolutionary Front led by its Chairman Oscar
Zamora Medinacelli, this evening.
</P>
<P>
Huang, also secretary of the Shanghai Municipal Committee of
the CPC, called Zamora an old friend of the CPC and Chinese
people, and spoke highly of his contribution to promoting
friendship between the parties and people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese FM Calls for Advance Research for Diplomatic Work
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan today called for advance
research in diplomacy to take into account the way that hegemonism
and power politics continue to expand.
</P>
<P>
Tang made the call at a gathering to address the heroic
achievements the Chinese embassy in Belgrade has made and the
three journalists killed in the U.S.-led NATO missile attack. "The
world has not enjoyed peace since the end of the Cold War," Tang
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
