<HEADLINE> India Denies Development of War-Like Situation With Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- New Delhi Wednesday dismissed
apprehensions of the development of a war-like situation between
India and Pakistan following the air strikes in the Kargil sector
of the disputed Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the External Affairs Ministry said in a press
briefing that India's military operations had been well inside the
line of actual control, not on the line or across it.
</P>
<P>
"The entire exercise has been to root out intruders" from the
Pakistan side, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Indian fighters and helicopters attacked the Kargil sector in
Kashmir to flush out alleged Pakistan-backed infiltrators who
India said had occupied ridges there.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman accused the Pakistan army of systematically
preparing these intrusions, saying they were in blatant violation
of the Simla Agreement between the two countries and the Lahore
Declaration signed by the prime ministers of the two neighbors
last February.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government was in touch with all foreign missions
here to explain to them the situation in Kargil and the reasons
for the air strikes by the Indian Air Force, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also charged that Pakistan had attempted to
change the status quo by force or otherwise, saying the Indian
armed forces would take all necessary actions to complete their
task of putting an end to this intrusion.
</P>
<P>
He said India had always desired to make every effort to build
a relationship of lasting peace, friendship and cooperation with
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, "there cannot be a resolution of complex
issues (between the two countries) as long as Pakistan continued
to engage in confrontational and hostile activities."
</P>
<P>
He told the press that directors general of military operations
of the two countries had established contact on the hotline.
</P>
</TEXT>
