<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Solve Water Shortage Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will slove the water
shortage problem before the end of the year 2000, a senior Cypriot
official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, National Resources and Environment Minister Costas
Themistocleous told reporters that in about 18 months, the Cypriot
government would have completed its desalination program and all
water restrictions imposed now would be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Water shortage has been a problem for many years on the Cyprus
island. Now Cyprus has only one desalination plant, of which the
maximum daily output is 40 million litres of water.
</P>
<P>
Environmental studies are under way for a second unit to be
sited outside the southern coastal town of Larnaca, and efforts
have been making for the construction of two smaller desalination
plants.
</P>
<P>
Themistocleous said the desalination plants "will allow us to
lift the water restriction measures being enforced."
</P>
<P>
He said the government had abandoned its plans to operate
mobile desalination units from June this year, because needs
could be satisfied through the water collected in dams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
