<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
Riyadh -- The number of manufacturing industrial firms in the
member countries of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) rose to 962,
involving investments of 30.5 billion U.S. dollars. The GCC is a
share-holder in these firms that employ some 125,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
About 57 percent of the joint ventures are located in the
United Arab Emirates while over 72 percent of the investments in
joint manufacturing industrial firms are in Saudi Arabia, the
Egyptian local daily Al-Alam Al-Youm reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The joint ventures contribute more than 50 percent to the
capital of the manufacturing industries while the foreign
contribution accounts for 36 percent, the daily quoted a report by
the Gulf Organization of Industrial Investments as saying.
</P>
<P>
Damascus -- The Syrian government is amending the Investment
Act No. 10 for 1991. It is also seeking to offer tax and non-tax
exemptions to the projects to be launched in rural areas with a
view to expanding the development scope countrywide, the Arab
daily Al-Hayat reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The value of the overseas investment in Syria did not exceed one
billion dollars in 1995, i.e. one percent of the investment
market in the country, a local economist said.
</P>
<P>
Beirut -- There is no indication of growing inflation in
Lebanon due to the fiscal stability policy, Governor of the
Central Bank of Lebanon (CBL) Riyadh Salamah was quoted by the
Arab daily Al-Hayat on Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Salamah pointed out that the inflation rate went down to less
than 5 percent last year, adding the fiscal policy of the CBL
"brought down the interest rates and controlled the monetary
inflows," he added.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has planned to spend a
total of 7.5 billion U.S. dollars on infrastructure projects
in the upcoming five years, the As Safir newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the five-year plan of the state-run Council
for Reconstruction and Development(CDR), some 4.1 billion dollars
will be used on projects currently underway and the rest on
projects to be carried out in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The CDR plan, which still needs the approval of the cabinet,
earmarks 1.26 billion dollars for infrastructure projects, 18.43
billion dollars for social projects, 88 million dollars for
productive sectors and 193 million dollars for administrative
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
