<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Bangkok Get Cleaner Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) will extend a
helping hand to the Bangkok Metropolitan Administration (BMA) and
other local agencies to implement an initiative to improve air
quality in the capital city, a WB statement said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at helping reduce health impact in a
cost-effective and environment-friendly manner, increasing public
awareness on the issue and strengthening long-term transport
planning, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The project objective would be achieved through a blend of
pollution control reduction measures, primarily in the urban
sector, and the formulation of a long-term strategy for transport
and other priority sub-sectors.
</P>
<P>
At a two-day workshop, which ended Wednesday in Pattaya, a
famous beach resort some 200 kilometers southeast of here, Bangkok
Governor Bhichit Rattakul said there is now a clear willingness of
all agencies to join forces and work together to ensure that
Bangkok citizens could breathe clean air.
</P>
<P>
Elimination of lead from gasoline in Thailand has been regarded
as an example for other countries to emulate, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, it claimed that these actions have been insufficient
to reverse the air pollution trend, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
