<HEADLINE> Britain, Argentina Begin Falklands Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Argentina on Wednesday
began to hold talks over the disputed Falkand Islands. The talks
were set to focus on restoring air links between the islands and
South America.
</P>
<P>
The British delegation was headed by junior Foreign Office
minister Tony Lloyd and the Argentine side was led by Foreign
Minister Guido Di Tella, a British Foreign Office spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said a statement would be issued at the end of the talks,
which began at 0900 GMT Wednesday and were expected to last about
two days.
</P>
<P>
Britain repeatedly said that there can be no discussion of the
sovereignty of the islands, which Argentina calls the Malvinas and
has claimed since 1833.
</P>
<P>
"Sovereignty is not on the agenda," the British spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem has repeatedly promised that
his country's flag will fly over the islands before his term
finishes at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, a war broke out between the two countries over the
sovereignty of the Falklands, which costed about 1,000 lives, most
of them Argentine servicemen.
</P>
<P>
The London talks, which are not expected to result in formal
decisions, were proposed by the British government at the request
of the Falklands Legislative Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals in Singapore Up 6.6 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Singapore
increased by 6.6 percent in April from a year earlier, totaling
523,928 with a large year-on-year hike from Indonesia and China,
the Singapore Tourism Board (STB) said in a press release
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
STB also said the increase brought to 2.19 million the total
tourist arrivals in the first four months of 1999, registering a
8.6-percent rise year-on-year over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from China, the sixth largest departure point, totaled
28,977, up 44 percent from a year ago, it said.
</P>
<P>
According to STB, Indonesia sent 78,633 visitors to Singapore
in April 1999, a 32-percent increase over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals from Indonesia in the first four months
totaled 353,570, up 34 percent from the same period a year earlier
and becoming the top market for Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Compared with April 1998, tourists from Malaysia rose by 10
percent to 40,226 in April 1999 while those from Japan fell by 3.1
percent to 52,404. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
