<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Britain Favor Peace Efforts to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Italy and Britain on Wednesday
expressed their "full support" to a meeting in Moscow of Finnish,
Russian and U.S. officials on seeking a political solution to the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, after meeting with his
visiting British counterpart Robin Cook on Wednesday,said that
Italy and Britain fully supported the peace efforts of Russian
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, who is holding talks in Moscow
Wednesday with U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and
European Union envoy and Finnish president Martti Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
Dini also explained that "the two countries fully support the
diplomatic efforts based on the Group of Eight (G8) proposals, but
we must be ready to enter Kosovo once an agreement is reached and
Belgrade withdraws its troops."
</P>
<P>
A peace plan, drawn up by Britain, Canada, France, Germany,
Italy, Japan, Russia and the United States, calls for the return
of refugees to Kosovo, the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces from the
Serbian province, the deployment of a peacekeeping force in Kosovo
and negotiations on a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
Dini said that "when an accord is reached, no time must be
wasted, NATO's decision to expand its ground forces reflects the
latest developments."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, British Defense Secretary George Robertson declared
that NATO troops could, if necessary, enter Kosovo without
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's agreement.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that "such a decision would have to be taken by the
Alliance and not just Great Britain."
</P>
<P>
Cook, who arrived here Wednesday morning, is scheduled to fly
to France and Germany Wednesday afternoon for further talks on the
Balkans conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
