<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Fingers Crossed for Pak-India Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The latest escalation of military
confrontation between India and Pakistan along the
720-kilometer-long Line of Control (LoC) in the disputed Kashmir
has cast a shadow over the official talks between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have committed themselves to the continuation
of high-level official talks aimed at settling all outstanding
issues, including the core dispute of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
However, tensions along the LoC "would bode ill for the efforts
to improve the atmosphere" between the two countries, Pakistan's
Foreign Ministry spokesman Tariq Altaf said amidst reports that
India has sent in reinforcements after two weeks of heavy
artillery duel along the LoC.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here from Kashmir, the Indian Air
Force Wednesday launched a series of air strikes to "clear
Pakistan-backed infiltrators" in the Kargil sector of
India-controlled Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Air Force is reported to have used various aircraft
including jet fighters and helicopters from various bases to
strike in Drass, Batalik and other regions in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Tension between the two estranged South Asian neighbors is
mounting these days because of the intense artillery dual that has
been going on uninterrupted for more than two weeks along the LoC
in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
At least 35 soldiers are reported to have been killed along
with scores of civilians on both sides in the renewed clashes in
Kargil and Drass sectors of the LoC which divides the Kashmir
region between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India have fought three wars, mainly over Kashmir,
since their simultaneous independence in 1947. Large-scale
military clashes erupted along the LoC between the two nations in
July last year after they respectively conducted nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The renewed cross-border shelling has ended a three-month
cease-fire that began before the Lahore Summit between the prime
ministers of the two countries in February.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here expressed doubt about the normalization process
to which both India and Pakistan are committed.
</P>
<P>
India's caretaker Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee paid a
historic visit to Pakistan in February this year and signed the
Lahore Declaration with his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The Lahore Declaration commits both countries to intensifying
their efforts to resolve their outstanding issues including the
Jammu and Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
India blamed Pakistan for the recent border flare-up by sending
a large number of heavily armed Muslim militants into its troubled
part of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
But Islamabad shrugged off the charge as a pretext "to justify
their unwarranted military action" against the Muslim militants.
</P>
<P>
India-controlled Kashmir has been the scene of insurgency for
the past 10 years. New Delhi accuses Islamabad of fomenting the
trouble but Pakistan denies the charge and says it only lends
political, diplomatic and moral support to "Kashmir freedom
fighters."
</P>
<P>
"It should be made clear to them (Indians) that to lay blame on
Pakistan or any effort or a misguided plan will be taken very very
seriously and consequences will lie on India," a report by the
Associated Press of Pakistan quoted army chief General Pervez
Musharaf as saying earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
His warning came as reports said India has placed four brigades
and two fighter-squadrons of the Indian Air Force on high alert
for possible strike operation in Kashmir's Kargil sector.
</P>
<P>
Similar stern statements were also heard from the Indian side.
</P>
<P>
Reports quoted Indian Ambassador to Pakistan G. Parthasarthy as
saying his country "will use weapons of its choice" to defend the
LoC.
</P>
<P>
However, diplomatic sources ruled out the possibility of a
full-fledged war between the two nations which last year stunned
the world with their tit-for-tat nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"It will remain localized and will be sorted out at the level
of military commanders (at the LoC)," an Islamabad-based diplomat
said.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the foreign ministers of the two
countries have proposed dates to each other for the expert-level
talks on nuclear-related issues.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign secretary-level talks are not expected to
take place until a new government takes power in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
"While India is facing a period of political uncertainty, we,
on our part, remain committed to carry the process forward in the
spirit of the Lahore Declaration," Prime Minister Sharif said in
his address at the National Defense College recently.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said Wednesday that Pakistan has
agreed in principle that the two countries should hold
expert-level talks before India's general elections and the
foreign secretary-level talks should be held after the polls.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts here believe that the normalization process
between Pakistan and India has suffered major setbacks due to the
recent military clashes along the LoC in the Kashmir region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
