<HEADLINE> Poll: Almost All Greeks Oppose NATO Bombing of Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Almost all Greeks opposed the NATO
bombing of Yugoslavia and the alliance's possible ground campaign
in the country, according to the findings of a poll released here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, which was conducted by the Panteios University on 1,
000 Greeks in the cities of Athens and Piraeus between April 29
and May 5, showed that at least 99.5 percent of those questioned
said they opposed NATO's air strikes against Yugoslavia while 99.3
percent were against a possible ground campaign by NATO in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
85 percent said that the reasons for the air strikes were to
show off the power of the United States. 70 percent believed that
the main culprit was U.S. President Bill Clinton, British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, NATO Commander Wesley Clark and NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana, and 25 percent said that these
leaders should be charged as war criminals.
</P>
<P>
80 percent said that they found the Greek news media objective
in reporting NATO bombing, and 56 percent believed that the Greek
government should have vetoed the NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
The poll also showed that 52 percent of Greeks said that the "
closest" people to them were now the Serbs while the English,
Americans and French were considered further back.
</P>
<P>
A previous poll had shown that 95 percent of Greeks were
opposed to the NATO bombing, which started on March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
