<HEADLINE> China Launches Campaign to Learn From Martyrs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Publicity Department of the
Chinese Communist Party Central Committee today launched a
campaign for people to learn from the three Chinese journalists
killed in the NATO missile attack on the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade early this month and those journalists still working
there.
</P>
<P>
The three victims, Shao Yunhuan of the Xinhua News Agency and
Xu Xinghu, Zhu Ying of the Beijing based Guangming Daily, have
already been honored with the title of "revolutionary martyrs" by
the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
"This campaign will be of great significance to our efforts to
improve our contingent of publicity and ideological work and do a
good job in various works at present," according to a circular
issued today to all departments engaged in publicity and
ideological work across China.
</P>
<P>
The circular praised the three deceased journalists and their
colleagues remaining in the battlefield of Yugoslavia as "having
reflected the fine mental outlook of Chinese journalists in the
new period" and having set an excellent example for those staying
at home.
</P>
<P>
"We should learn from their loyalty to the Party, the
motherland and the people, from their selfless dedication to their
career and duty, as well as from their heroic spirit of daring to
fight against brutality and defying the threat of death," said the
circular.
</P>
<P>
It urged all news media and other publicity and ideological
organs to focus on spreading and encouraging patriotism among the
people, and also to try and "expose and criticize in a profound
manner the hypocritical and reactionary nature of the so-called
'democracy', 'human rights, 'humanity' and 'press freedom'
preached by the U.S.-led NATO".
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, we must adhere to the principle of mainly doing
positive and inspiring publicity so as to promote unity and
stability, and try to make new contributions to promoting reform
and development, maintaining social stability and the advancement
of the great cause of building socialism with Chinese
characteristics into the 21st century," it concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
