<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Minister on Asian Financial Crisis Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Myanmar government
official admitted Wednesday that Asia's currency and financial
crisis has had some effect on Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Although the country's undeveloped capital market, tight
foreign exchange control and the non-convertible and non-tradable
local currency spared the country from the initial financial
crisis shock,
Myanmar was impacted by the "contagion" effect as the crisis
deepened and turned into an economic turmoil, Brigadier-General
D.O. Abel, minister at the Office of the Chairman of the Myanmar
State Peace and Development Council said.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address at the opening session of a two-day
ASEAN business forum here, Abel recalled that Myanmar achieved a
steady economic growth rate prior to the on-set of the financial
crisis, saying Myanmar's gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate
averaged 7.5 percent between fiscal 1992 and fiscal 1995.
</P>
<P>
The two-day business forum is held in conjunction with the 56th
Council Meeting of Chambers of Commerce and Industry (CCI) of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The annual growth rate fell from 6.4 to 5.7 and to 5.6 percent
in the fiscal years of 1996,1997 and 1998 respectively, he
complained, also attributing the decline to unfavorable weather
conditions arising from effect of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the most adversely affected is foreign
direct investment (FDI), with ASEAN investments falling by 70
percent in 1998. ASEAN investments accounted for almost 60 percent
of the total prior to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
As recovery measures, he stated, intensified efforts are made
in the agricultural sector with new arable land developed and the
private sector growing cash crops on a large scale to ensure food
security.
</P>
<P>
On the financial side of the recovery measures, he added,
Myanmar has tightened budgetary control, disallowing new large
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
On the impact on trade, he denied that the crisis had a
spill-over effect on Myanmar's trade as 45 percent of the
country's trade is with ASEAN nations and is complementary rather
than competitive. Trade with these countries has been increasing
over the past three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also denied that the country's tourism industry has been
affected, saying tourist arrivals increased by 5 percent in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
