<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Speed Train Locomotive Hits the Rails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China's first high speed train,
which can reach speeds of 200 kilometers an hour, has come off the
production line today in Changsha, the capital city of central
China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Only a few countries in the world are now capable of
manufacturing locomotives which can hit such speeds.
</P>
<P>
Two years of research and design work on the locomotive, which
looks like the head of a bullet, was carried out by Zhuzhou
Electrical Locomotive Plant and a number of engine and railway
institutions and colleges.
</P>
<P>
The train will run on the Guangzhou-Shenzhen semi-express
railway route.
</P>
<P>
Now railway sources say China is planning to build locomotives
that can hit speeds of more than 250 km by early in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
Railway transport in the country has long lagged behind the
pace of economic growth and in recent years, the Ministry of
Railways has been making efforts to increase the speed of trains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
