<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Court Adjourns Case of Rwandan Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The extradition case
concerning Bernard Ntuyahaga, a former army officer wanted by both
Rwanda and Belgium for his role in the 1994 Rwanda genocide, has
been adjourned to next month because the counsel for him has not
got prepared.
</P>
<P>
Appearing at the Kisutu Resident Magistrate's Court in Dar es
Salaam, the lawyer, Jwain Mwaikusa, said he was assigned to defend
for Ntuyahaga only last week.
</P>
<P>
He further said he met his client just ten minutes before the
court heard the case in the morning and he has not got time to
read legal documents related to it.
</P>
<P>
In addition, as a teacher at the Law Department of the
University of Dar es Salaam, Mwaikusa said his students start
their final exams this week and he will have to mark the
examination papers later.
</P>
<P>
He said the matter at his school will be fixed in the week
beginning June 14. "It's my request we begin hearing on the
15th," he added.
</P>
<P>
Projestus Rugazia, the principal resident magistrate, agreed to
the request and announced to hear the case on that day. It has
been the fourth time for the court to adjourn the case.
</P>
<P>
Before that, Ntuyahaga is expected to appear in the court on
June 8. According to the Tanzanian legal proceedings, a case must
be mentioned within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Major Ntuyahaga, former head of logistics at Kigali military
camp in Rwanda, allegedly murdered former Rwandan Prime Minister
Agathe Uwiningiyimana and 10 Belgium U.N. peacekeepers escorting
her in the 1994 Rwandan genocide.
</P>
<P>
The 47-year-old man is wanted by both Rwanda and Belgium for
extradition and trial.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have requested the Tanzanian government to hand
over the accused to their countries for trial. The Tanzanian
government said it will abide by court ruling.
</P>
<P>
Ntuyahaga was handed to Tanzania in March this year after the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR), created by the
United Nations Security Council in the Arusha town in north
Tanzania, dropped charges of genocide and crimes against humanity
against him and set him free.
</P>
<P>
The accused, however, was re-arrested shortly after he was
released. The Tanzanian police caught him in the name of illegal
entry as he came into the country without going through normal
immigration procedures.
</P>
<P>
Mwaikusa told reporters after Wednesday's court session that
what he is trying to do is to keep Ntuyahaga in Tanzania as a
refugee and not to be extradited to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"You know, Tanzania has many refugees," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
