<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AFC Keeps Ban on Chinese and Iranian Strikers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Football
Confederation (AFC) announced Wednesday that they had rejected
appeals by two top players against a one-year ban.
</P>
<P>
AFC secretary-general Peter Velappan said the AFC had received
appeals from governments, clubs and thousands of fans for a one-
year ban against China's Hao Haidong and Iran's Mohamad Ali Karimi
to be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Hao was also fined 2,000 dollars for spitting at a linesman at
Bangkok's Asian Games in December, while Karimi was fined 3,000
dollars for assaulting a referee at the Dunhill Cup in Vietnam in
February.
</P>
<P>
"The committee looked at these cases as very serious. We don't
allow any referee or assistant referee to be assaulted. The
appeals by the two associations have been turned down," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They will be suspended from all football for a year. They have
served three months, there is another nine months to go." 
</P>
</TEXT>
