<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stamp Market Booming in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- When the Tibet Stamp Collection
Company was first established in 1983 there were no more than one
hundred stamp collectors in this southwest China Tibet Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
However, ever since then the company has been trying to create
public awareness among people by sponsoring lectures, auctions and
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
Now there are some 20,000 local collectors including over 4,000
members of over 30 stamp collecting associations.
</P>
<P>
The company has also issued nearly 100 philately products
including commemorative envelopes, postcards, memorial stamps and
albums, all with typical Tibetan characteristics.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan-made postcards and memorial envelops featuring the
Tibetan landscape and temples have been bestsellers for years.
</P>
<P>
To date, Tibet has issued 15 sets of envelopes and postcards,
while the central postal authorities have published six sets of
Tibet dedicated postage stamps since 1952.
</P>
<P>
This year, a series of postal products have been and will be
issued to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the democratic
reform in Tibet, which was launched in 1959.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
