<HEADLINE> Nigerian Outgoing Head Pledges Readiness for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar declared Tuesday that he was ready for any
corruption investigations into his 10-month administration, the
Nigerian Tribune newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The head of state said this against the increasingly tense
criticism that high officials in his regime have been looting the
federal treasury.
</P>
<P>
He said he was satisfied with the performance of everybody that
served during his regime.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar was quoted as saying that he was ready to stand up for
the integrity of members of his cabinet and the Provisional Ruling
Council, which is to disband Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But the outgoing Head of State told the British Broadcasting
Corporation (BBC) on a interview Tuesday that "It is good to give
little gifts, but then gifts of high financial magnitude, we'll
begin to wonder where the resources come from, they must have come
from sources that somebody really needs to think about. Then this
needs to be looked into."
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also extended thanks to the provisional ruling council
members for their contribution to the stability in the most
populous African country.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's foreign currency reserve has quickly collapsed to a
dangerous sum of three billion dollars from seven billion at the
end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Some Nigerian people as well as many international
organizations have been constantly criticizing officials in
Abubakar-led government for corruption and looting the treasury.
</P>
</TEXT>
