<HEADLINE> Disease Wipes Out Young Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, May 26 (Xinhua) -- As many as 60,000 young trees in
northeast China have died of a plant disease called "rotten willow
disease".
</P>
<P>
In Harbin alone, the provincial capital of Heilongjiang
Province, about 10,000 young trees, mostly willows and poplars,
have died or are dying of the disease, which has caused a direct
economic loss of 2.2 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A similar disaster has also been reported in Qiqihar,
Mudanjiang, Daqing, all in Heilongjiang Province, and in Changchun,
capital of Jilin Province, as well as in Shenyang, capital of
Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that the abnormal climate from late autumn of
last year through to spring this year weakened the growth of the
trees and led to the rampant reproduction of a parasitic bacteria
attacking the trees.
</P>
<P>
Relevant departments of different localities have taken
measures including felling and destroying seriously sick trees,
spraying pesticides on healthy or slightly affected trees to
prevent further contagion of the disease.
</P>
<P>
The city government of Harbin, for instance, has allocated one
million yuan for curing the tree disease. While felling and
destroying 6,000 doomed trees, city government officials have also
whitewashed all the trees lining streets and courtyards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
