<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe To Launch Road Repair Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
embark on a 176-million-U.S. dollar drive to rehabilitate its
badly damaged road network, the Ministry of Transport and Energy
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The project will start next year when the government finally
establishes the Road Fund, which is meant to oversee the
transformation of the country' s roads into a sound network, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest report on the Road Sector Reform and
Development Program released by the ministry in Harare, more than
half of the country's roads are badly damaged, some of them due to
incessant rains which pounded the country during the last rainy
season.
</P>
<P>
The situation had been further worsened by the fact that
funding for the road rehabilitation and maintenance had dwindled
by more than 25 percent over the years.
</P>
<P>
The Road Fund will be expected to derive its revenue through
road user charges to cater for the full routine and periodic
maintenance of the entire road network.
</P>
<P>
The fund will require about 36.8 million dollars annually,
which is three times more than what is currently being spent.
</P>
<P>
The private sector will be expected to play a key role in the
implementation of the program, said the report, adding that the
road repair drive would create 30,000 new jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
