<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Agrees to Renew Oil-for-Food Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi government has agreed to
renew the oil-for-food program for another six months, or the
sixth phase, well-informed sources told Xinhua on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said on conditions of anonymity that Iraq had
agreed officially to extend the oil-for-food program for another
six months, adding that Iraq informed the U.N. of its decision
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has not formally announced its acceptance
of the extension of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the U.N. Security Council agreed unanimously to
extend the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program for the sixth phase,
starting on May 26.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has voiced its worry several times that the U.S. and
Britain are trying to make the oil-for-food program an
alternative to the lifting of sanctions imposed on the country
following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi newspapers have carried articles recently, declaring that
the oil-for-food program failed to alleviate the suffering of the
Iraqi people, and that the only solution to the Iraqi issue is to
lift the nine-year-old sanctions immediately and unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iraq-U.N. memorandum of understanding, since
December 1996 the U.N. has allowed Iraq to export limited amount
of oil in every six months to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian supplies for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
Starting from the fourth phase of the oil-for-food program, the
U.N. raised the ceiling of the amount of oil Iraq is allowed to
export to 5.26 billion U.S. dollars from 2 billion dollars for the
first three phases.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was just able to export some 3 billion dollars worth of
oil in the fourth phase due to the sagging oil prices on the world
markets and the severe lack of oil spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi oil officials have said that if necessary oil spare parts
are available, Iraq can increase its oil production to the
pre-sanctions level of 3.25 million barrels per day (bpd) from the
current 2.65 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long accused the U.S. and British representatives
in the U.N. Sanctions Committee of blocking its contracts
concluded with foreign companies, holding the two countries
responsible for the deterioration of the humanitarian situation in
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
