<HEADLINE> HK Operates Stringent System of Strategic Trade Control: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) Government spokesman said here
Wednesday that Hong Kong is operating an autonomous and stringent
system of strategic trade control under the principle of "one
country, two systems".
</P>
<P>
The remark was made in response to the just published report by
U.S. Republican Representative Christopher Cox which alleged that
China had used Hong Kong as an illegal transshipment point to
obtain sensitive American military technology.
</P>
<P>
"Under the Basic Law, Hong Kong is a separate customs territory
which has full autonomy in regulating the import and export of
goods, including strategic commodities. Our strategic trade
control system is backed up by transparent laws, comprehensive
licensing requirements and vigorous enforcement. All companies,
regardless of their background, are subject to the same set of
rules and regulations," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We maintain close cooperation with our major trading partners
in combating the illegal diversion of strategic commodities. We
follow the highest standard of control practiced by international
non-proliferation regimes. We are determined to continue doing so
for our own economic interests," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
