<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Gears Up Government Procurement Drive (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China moved one step closer to
opening its government procurement market to the outside world by
adopting the first national guideline in this respect recently.
</P>
<P>
The Provisional Regulations on Administration of Government
Procurement issued by the Ministry of Finance incorporates
international norms in a framework of policy and principles of
establishing an open, just and fair government procurement system
in the future.
</P>
<P>
"The provisional regulations pave the way for China to open its
government procurement market and access the international market
in the future," said Zhang Tong, deputy director general of the
Budget Department of the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The provisional regulations establish rules for government
procurement in terms of the entities, methods, public tendering
procedures and legal liabilities.
</P>
<P>
China will open its government procurement market to members of
the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) organization by 2020.
If it joins the World Trade Organization (WTO), it will also open
the market to other countries and regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that China is striving to grasp the last chance to
set up and rein-in its government procurement mechanism so as to
prepare local enterprises for foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
The provisional regulations stipulate that governments at all
levels are not allowed to procure foreign goods and services
without approval by relevant authorities. The regulations also
exclude state-owned enterprises from the entities to be put under
the government procurement system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Gears Up Government Procurement Drive (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
So far, all but three autonomous regions have started
government procurement on a trial basis. In 1998, more than 2,000
procurement orders were placed by the provincial governments,
worth 3.1 billion yuan. Over a dozen local governments have also
promulgated their own regulations in this respect.
</P>
<P>
However, China is yet to promulgate national laws on government
procurement. The provisional regulations released by the Ministry
of Finance recently serve as standard guidelines for the local
rules, which sometimes are not in conformity with international
norms. On the other hand, it leaves room for local governments to
promulgate more detailed regulations according to local conditions.
</P>
<P>
Now Chinese authorities are in the process of drafting formal
regulations on government procurement and the Government
Procurement Law.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the establishment of a government procurement
system will greatly increase the central government's leverage of
the economy. It will shift the control of procurement money from
various government institutions to a centralized system. This will
actually then have an effect on economic growth and industrial
development through adjusting the total volume and scope of
procurement.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance estimates that through public tendering
of supply of goods and services, the government will save at least
30 billion yuan of tax payers' money every year and minimize
misuse of public funds. It is reported that 80 percent of the
biggest embezzlement cases in the country involve an inadequate
transparency of government expenditures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
