<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NRP Wants to Join Barak's Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Israel's National Religious Party
(NRP) will join the coalition government led by Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak if it is asked for, said NRP leader
Yitzhak Levy Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the coalition talks with the One
Israel's negotiating team in Herzliya near Tel Aviv, Levy said
that Barak, leader of One Israel, has expressed his desire to ask
NRP to join the coalition and NRP is ready to enter into further
negotiations with One Israel to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
NRP's future negotiations with One Israel, which won 26 seats
in the 120-member Knesset (parliament) in the May 17 election,
will be conducted on one condition that NRP takes the education
portfolio of the next government, Levy said.
</P>
<P>
NRP won only five seats of the 15th Knesset in the election as
compared to nine it held in the former parliament.
</P>
<P>
Local media attributed this to NRP's hardline policy towards
the peace process which caused the Likud-led government to fall
early this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, One Israel's negotiating team concluded its talks
Wednesday with the Yisrael Beiteinu (Israel Our Home) headed by
Avigdor Leiberman, which also expressed its interests of joining
Barak's coalition.
</P>
<P>
Leiberman, former Director-General of the incumbent Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office, formed this new party before
the elections during which it won four Knesset seats. The party's
supporters were mainly Russian-speaking immigrants from the former
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
"The Yisrael Beiteinu has a common ground with One Israel
and there will be no problem for it to join the coalition
headed by Barak," Yuri Stern, head of the party's negotiation
team said after the talks.
</P>
<P>
So far, One Israel's negotiating team has concluded its first
round of coalition talks with all 15 political parties which have
won Knesset seats and will submit its report to Barak for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
The second round of talks are expected to be conducted soon.
</P>
<P>
The Central Election Committee officially announced the
election results Tuesday evening. Barak has 45 days to form his
government and submit the cabinet lists to the Knesset for
approval under the election law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
