<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Israeli Militia to Withdraw From S.Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Israel's proxy militia South Lebanon
Army(SLA) is planning to evacuate south Lebanon's Christian town
of Jezzine within the next few days, the Voice of the People radio
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted security sources as saying that
Maj. Gen. Antoine Lahd, the militia's commander, had formally
notified Israeli Defense Minister Moshe Arens of his decision to
pull out the SLA garrison from Jezzine within days.
</P>
<P>
The sources said senior officials of the SLA's regiment in
Jezzine have already evacuated their families into the Israeli
occupied border zone in south Lebanon, which Israel declared as a
"security zone" in 1985 to prevent cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Jezzine, Lebanon's largest Christian town in the south, has
never been incorporated into the border enclave although it has
long been policed by the SLA.
</P>
<P>
The town sits on the northern rim of a salient jutting some 10
kilometers northward from the border zone.
</P>
<P>
Observers said Lahd's reported decision to pullback was largely
the result of escalated guerrilla's bombing attacks around the
town, whose population has dwindled from 35,000 before the 1975
outbreak of Lebanon's 15-year civil war to 5,000 at present.
</P>
<P>
Some 15 SLA officers and militiamen and 20 civilians have been
killed in bombing ambushes around the town in the past nine months
by Lebanese guerrillas, notably the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, which is leading a guerrilla war to oust Israeli
troops and SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Media reports speculated the militia commander would personally
visit Jezzine in the next 48 hours to discuss his decision with
the town's notables.
</P>
<P>
Lahd, along with his 2,500 followers, is termed in Lebanon as
traitors and has been sentenced to death in absentia by a Lebanese
military court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
