<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000 Black Australians Mark National Sorry Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- About 2,000 indigenous Australians
in Sydney, Melbourne and Canberra marked the first anniversary of
National Sorry Day Wednesday to commemorate victims of the
country's white assimilation policy earlier this century.
</P>
<P>
In Canberra, the country's capital, around 1,000 people
gathered at Australian Parliament House to launch The Journey of
Healing between 300,000 black Australians and 18 million white
Australians.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was attended by government, opposition and minor
party figures.
</P>
<P>
National Sorry Day began last year when thousands of
Australians acknowledged the consequences of the government's
policies forcibly removing aboriginal children, better known as
the stolen generations, from their families during 1910-1970.
</P>
<P>
The children, totaling approximately 100,000, had been raised
at government-funded welfare centers or churches, with many of
them losing contact with their families for good.
</P>
<P>
But the Australian federal government, including Prime Minister
John Howard, has repeatedly refused to apologize for the stolen
generations, saying his government cannot be held responsible for
the actions of past governments.
</P>
<P>
In Australia's biggest city of Sydney, about 800 people have
taken part in a march to mark National Sorry Day.
</P>
<P>
The parade featured colorful cardboard cutouts of hands
representing reconciliation between indigenous and non-indigenous
people and a giant rainbow serpent led the march.
</P>
<P>
In Melbourne, more than 300 people marched through central
Melbourne Wednesday to commemorate the anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Members of the stolen generations and other indigenous as well
as non-indigenous Australians reflected on their history at the
end of the march.
</P>
<P>
Larry Walsh, who was part of the stolen generations, said it
had taken him nearly 46 years to recover, and he still felt he had
not quite recovered.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony ended with traditional music and dancing.
</P>
<P>
Some political figures in Australia, including Australian
Governor-General William Deane, have been calling for more efforts
for the country to achieve reconciliation between the indigenous
and non-indigenous Australians.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the governor-general again highlighted the plight of
indigenous Australians and his concerns about the reconciliation
process.
</P>
<P>
"These days, it is sometimes difficult not to feel discouraged
- even depressed - about the slow course of the reconciliation
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
At a national reconciliation conference in 1997, he apologized
over the stolen Aboriginal children when Prime Minister John
Howard had refused. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
