<HEADLINE> West African Community Recognizes New Nigerien </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) has recognized Niger's new military
leader, Major Daouda Wanke, after a heated debate at the emergency
session of foreign ministers in Togolese capital Lome.
</P>
<P>
A final communique issued by the meeting started Monday said
that the ECOWAS "stressed the need for an independent committee of
enquiry that would look into the death of President Ibrahim
Mainassara Bare."
</P>
<P>
Mainassara was killed on April 9 this year by members of his
guards at the start of a military coup in Niger, The Guardian
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, a row broke out among the foreign ministers
of the 16-member ECOWAS over whether to recognize or isolate the
new military leadership in Niger which came to power after the
killing of President Mainassara.
</P>
<P>
After a marathon debate lasting until 3:00 a.m. Tuesday, the
ECOWAS ministers moved not to adopt the draft resolution which
called for Niger's isolation until "democratic elections" were
held there.
</P>
<P>
However, the final communique of the meeting, which was
designed to discuss regional insecurity in Niger, Guinea Bissau
and Sierra Leone, has warned that it would deny recognition to
future coup makers in the west African sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Guinea Bissau where President Joao Bernardo Vieira
was ousted by a junta earlier this month, the ECOWAS agreed that
some 600 soldiers from west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG
would be pulled out of the country.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS also called on the junta to allow safe passage of
President Vieira and his family who are holed up in the Portuguese
embassy in capital Bissau "to any country of their choice."
</P>
<P>
On the conflict in Sierra Leone, the ECOWAS appealed to the
government and rebels delegations to sit down at the negotiating
table to "demonstrate flexibility and spirit of compromise and
conciliation". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
