<HEADLINE> Bangladeshis to Have Cricket Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Overjoyed Bangladeshis, whose cricket
team won its first victory at the century's last Cricket World Cup
in England on Monday, will soon have a stadium exclusively for
cricket, a press report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Bangabandhu National Stadium, previously known as Dhaka
Stadium, is likely to be given to the Bangladesh Cricket Board (
BCB)for the development of cricket, Deputy Minister for Local
Government and Rural Development and BCB President Saber Hossain
Chowdhury said Tuesday, The Independent daily newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Time has come for Bangladesh to have an exclusive cricket
stadium, and Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina has assured the BCB of
such a stadium, said Chowdhury, who is now in London leading the
cricket team.
</P>
<P>
Cricket is the most popular sport in Bangladesh, and this is
the first time that the Bangladeshi squad has been qualified to
contest with 11 other world-class teams in the Cricket World Cup.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, an expatriate Bangladeshi living in London
presented 500 pound sterling cash prize to each of player of the
15-member squad for their maiden Cricket World Cup victory against
Scotland, the report said.
</P>
<P>
And Bangladesh Road Transport Corporation (BRTC) announced here
Tuesday that it would award 1,000 taka for each run taken by
Bangladeshi batsmen who would be able to hit half century or more
in the team's coming matches. Two players, Minhazul Abedin and
Mehrah Hussain Opee, who secured 68 and 64 runs respectively in
the past two matches, would also receive 68,000 taka and 64,000
taka from the (BRTC
</P>
<P>
On May 15, Hasina announced lucrative cash awards for the
Bangladesh national cricket squad.
</P>
<P>
Every member of the squad would get 50,000 taka for their first
win and another 100,000 taka for every other victory of the first
phase league match, and in addition to these, a batsman who hits a
century and a bowler who bags four wickets would be richer by 100,
000 taka, and any cricketer of the squad who wins Man of the Match
would earn 100,000 taka.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 World Cup Cricket offers a total prize money of 1
million U.S. dollars, the largest amount ever in the sport, with
300,000 dollars for the champions will get, 150,000 dollars for
the runners-up and 100,000 dollars each for the losing semi-
finalists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
