<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Explain Ozone Losses over Qinghai-Tibet Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- New studies by Chinese scientists
indicate that particular thermodynamic effects have caused ozone
depletion over the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Zou Han, a researcher from the Institute of Atmospheric Physics
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said that a recent study shows
that the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau is a major geothermal source for
the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
"And as a result, air with a low content of ozone is heated and
rises to the ozone layer and dilutes its density," said the
scientist.
</P>
<P>
Gao Dengyi, former vice-director of the institute and an expert
in this field, said that vegetation on the plateau has decreased
rapidly in recent years, and large areas of rock are exposed. As a
result, a great amount of heat is reflected into the atmosphere in
spring, summer and autumn.
</P>
<P>
Zou Han said that similar phenomenon can also be found in other
large mountain ranges such as the Rocky Mountain in the United
States and the Andes Mountains in South America.
</P>
<P>
Spectral analysis of the data sent back from satellite surveys
shows that the ozone content over the plateau is lower than other
regions at the same latitude.
</P>
<P>
Observations have shown that the depletion is more rapid in
spring, approaching ten percent of the total volume, and most
serious at 18 kilometers above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have also found that the formation of the monsoons
in South Asia has close connections with the ozone loss over the
plateau.
</P>
<P>
Ozone is regarded as one of the protective green houses that
scientists believe modifies the strength of ultraviolet radiation
reaching the earth.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the natural landform, the disappearance of
forests and large scale urbanization are other major causes of
ozone loss, according to the scientists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Couple Climb Mt. Qomolangma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Swedish climber Thomas Sjogren
and his wife Dina Sjogren on Wednesday became the first couple to
scale the 8,848-meter Mount Qomolangma from the Nepali side, the
Nepali Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation announced.
</P>
<P>
Hugo R. Barroso and Corlos G. Pereda from Mexico also climbed
the world's tallest mountain with seven Nepalese Sherpas including
Babu Chhiri Sherpa, who set another record of climbing the summit
two times in the same season after establishing earlier this
season a record of staying at the summit for 21 hours, the
ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
All the summiters left the South Col (8,000m) at 9 o'clock
Tuesday evening and reached the top at 9:15 Wednesday morning.
They all stayed on the top for 30 minutes before retreating to the
South Col, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It said they are from the Swedish '99 International Qomolangma
Expedition led by Tina Sjogren, a 40-year-old businesswoman from
Stockholm, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
The spring season for mountaineering in Nepal began on March 1
and will end on May 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
