<HEADLINE> Fluoro Test in Australia Lights Up Early Signs of Lung Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A new test in which the bronchial
tubes are probed with fluorescent light may lead to detection of
lung cancer before it becomes invasive, the Australian Associated
Press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fluorescence bronchoscopy, used at only 30 medical centers
worldwide, is being tried at Princess Alexandra (PA) Hospital in
Brisbane, the third biggest city in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Respiratory physician Dr. David Fielding said the test could
pick up very early and small cancers which glowed red, compared
with healthy tissue which shone green, when viewed through a fiber
optic tube passed through the airways.
</P>
<P>
"Virtually all cancers present late. Only 13 percent of
patients with lung cancer survive five years, including those who
we get early enough to operate on," he said.
</P>
<P>
"By detecting cancers early we will be able to ablate them
completely, raising the five-year survival to around 95 percent,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
A study published in the journal, Chest, showed fluorescence
bronchoscopy had a six-fold increase in sensitivity over
conventional bronchoscopy for detecting superficial lung cancers.
</P>
<P>
The challenge was now to find a good method of sorting out high
risk patients from the general community, so they could be
screened with the new type of bronchoscope, Fielding said.
</P>
<P>
Diagnosis still requires a biopsy.
</P>
<P>
"Lung cancer is the commonest cause of cancer deaths among all
ages over 40," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
