<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Better Sunshine Blocking Cream Developed in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Australian scientists have
discovered a way to make zinc cream transparent and twice as
protective against harmful rays from the Sun.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Terry Turney from the Commonwealth Scientific and
Industrial Research Organization's (CSIRO) manufacturing science
and technology division, said that by reducing the size of
particles of the active ingredient, zinc oxide, the cream-like
sunscreen gave better coverage.
</P>
<P>
Australia ranks first in the world in terms of the incidence of
skin cancer due to depletion of ozone layer over Australia and
cream-like products to block harmful rays from the Sun are widely
used in summer time in this sunshine country.
</P>
<P>
Zinc oxide particles are normally about 250 nanometers but the
CSIRO treatment reduces them to as small as 10 nanometers and
gives more control over their surface chemistry.
</P>
<P>
"We can get them down to 1,000 times smaller than the diameter
of a human hair," Turney said at a forum at University of
Technology in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Zinc creams work by physically blocking UVB rays which cause
redness and burning, as well as UVA rays which lead to
photoageing.
</P>
<P>
The use of ultrafine particles means fewer rays can get through
to the skin, he said.
</P>
<P>
Normal particles both absorb and scatter light, which is why
zinc cream looks white.
</P>
<P>
"We're already running tests with several of the world's
leading cosmetics companies overseas and we expect there to be a
good export market there," Turney said.
</P>
<P>
Early versions of such sunscreens are already on the market,
but there will be a major push next summer after the production of
45 tons of the product, called Sunsorb. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
