<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Arab Parties to Enter Coalition? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Arab parties concluded
their first round of coalition talks with the negotiating team of
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak Tuesday, but no decision was made
on joining the new government.
</P>
<P>
All the three Arab parties, namely the United Arab List (UAL),
Hadash and Balad, had mobilized their supporters to vote for One
Israel leader Barak in the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
The Arab votes, which numbered nearly 1 million out of the 4.3
million eligible ballots, constituted a decisive factor for
Barak's victory and even One Israel has admitted the fact.
</P>
<P>
The three Arab parties reiterated their positions for joining
the coalition at Tuesday's talks.
</P>
<P>
Though the UAL, comprising the Islamic Movement and the
Democratic Arab Party (DAP), expressed its desire for a minister
portfolio as a full partner of a possible coalition, it opposes
the entry of the Likud, the National Religious Party and other
right-wing factions.
</P>
<P>
"We expressed our stance, that we supported Barak in order to
bring down the incumbent Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
change the government and its lines--something in which the Arab
community played an important part," said DAP leader Wahab
Darawshe after Tuesday's talks.
</P>
<P>
"We also made it clear that we are prepared to be full and
equal partners in a coalition with guidelines that we can live
with," he added.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the UAL, Israel's communist party Hadash does not see
itself becoming a member of the coalition, and this feeling was
strengthened after the party's meeting with Barak's negotiating
team.
</P>
<P>
Hadash spokesman Dror Nissan, who participated in the talks,
said that they had a distinct impression that prime purpose of
Barak's negotiating team was to "listen and make notes."
</P>
<P>
"If the Likud and the NRP are in the coalition, we will
definitely be in the opposition... and we will obviously support
moves to promote the peace process and all interests of the
Israeli Arab sector, but all other matters would be considered
individually and on their merits," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Leader of Balad Azmi Bishara, who withdrew from the race for
prime minister just before the voting, said after the talks that
it is highly unlikely Balad will join a Barak-led coalition even
without the Likud or the NRP, in the light of the comments made on
Jerusalem and other issues by Barak.
</P>
<P>
Barak said that he will move ahead the peace talks with the
Palestinians, but there would be no return to the 1967 border, no
foreign military presense in the west of the Jordan River, and
Jerusalem will be under Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
All three Arab parties called on Barak to state publicly his
commitment to the full implementation of all signed agreements
with the Palestinians, including the Wye accords, and to agree to
resume negotiations with Syria from where the talks were left off
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Barak defeated Netanyahu by 56.3 percent to 43.7 percent and he
has 45 days to form a new government since the official results of
the elections were announced. Barak promised to establish a
broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
The coalition talks continued Wednesday between Barak's
negotiating team and NRP and other parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No More of "Human Rights Above State Sovereignty" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- As the U.S.-led NATO bombardment of
Yugoslavia under the pretext of humanitarianism has created an
unprecedented humanitarian disaster in the Post-War history, it is
time now to put an end to the fallacy that human rights are above
state sovereignty cooked up by the United States and its major
allies.
</P>
<P>
The wanton bombing of Yugoslavia by the U.S.-led NATO has
lasted more than two months, leaving it a devastated land and its
people in misery and suffering, with an exodus of over one
million refugees. In face of the largest catastrophe in Europe
since the end of World War II, people all over the world,
including the American people, have determinedly called for peace.
But, on the other hand, NATO leaders have plausibly argued that
they launched the bombing to stop a humanitarian disaster. This is
a profound confusing of right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
In fact, this fallacy that human rights are above state
sovereignty has been used by the United States and its major
allies as a justification for their extremely cruel acts of
aggression.
</P>
<P>
This fallacy sells the idea that "human rights know no borders,
" "human rights are not part of the internal affairs of nations,"
"the principle of non-interference in the internal affairs of
others is not applicable on the human rights issue," etc.
</P>
<P>
Its producers have even become bold enough to claim that "we
might not be very far away from the time that undemocratic
countries or countries which do not care much about the respect of
human rights will not be viewed as sovereign countries."
</P>
<P>
This is indeed a logic of gangster; and its producers are
actually trying to find excuses for the United States to bully the
weak nations by sheer strength, to wantonly interfere in their
internal affairs and implement its gunboat diplomacy in the world.
</P>
<P>
The fallacy, by placing human rights above the sovereignty of
nations, fundamentally reverses the relationship between the two.
</P>
<P>
It is known to all that only by having national sovereignty can
people have their human rights guaranteed. Having suffered a great
deal from imperialist aggression and oppression in history,
peoples of the Third World countries are fully aware that, once
losing sovereignty, they are slaves to be trampled upon by others,
let alone the enjoyment of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Both history and reality of the international community have
proven that sovereignty is the basis for the realization of human
rights and interference in it is violation of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Sovereignty is the supreme power of nations and an independent
political authority internationally. Sovereignty, the power of a
nation to decide its domestic and foreign policies on its own will
and to handle all internal and international affairs free of
foreign interference, is actually the collective human rights of a
country.
</P>
<P>
Thus, it is untenable that the United States does not
understand that to spread the fallacy is spreading nonsense. For
a long time, the United States has given enormous publicity to the
"protection of human rights" internationally and acted as "human
rights judge," while itself is troubled by serious problems of
human rights at home.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.S. media, sentiment against foreign
immigration in the United States has been running high over recent
years and racial discrimination has become increasingly rampant.
</P>
<P>
The number of racist organizations in the country soared to 474
in 1997, an increase of 20 percent over the previous year. These
organizations have engaged themselves in such criminal activities
as burning down minority churches, damaging minority property and
killing minority people in apparent violation of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Then, in its logic, will the United States allow other
countries to bomb Washington or other cities, "mistakenly" kill
innocents and destroy infrastructures such as hospitals, schools,
power plants, highways and bridges for "protection of human rights
"?
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, by advocating the fallacy, the United
States is intended to seek hegemony under the pretext of
humanitarianism, having nothing to do with the protecting of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
The Times newspaper of Britain, commenting on a new doctrine of
the U.S.-led NATO on interference in the internal affairs of other
countries, said on March 29, "The new doctrine has two leading
characteristics. It extends the justification for war from self-
defense to defense of human rights inside another state. It leaves
the judgment to the individual nation or alliance, and does not
refer it to the United Nations, or any other international body.
It thereby removes both consensus and certainty from international
law."
</P>
<P>
By the same token, the outrageous bombing of Yugoslavia by the
U.S.-led NATO is downright hegemonism.
</P>
<P>
As early as in the Cold-War era, human rights were used by the
United States as a major pretext to interfere in the internal
affairs of others. While preaching profusely about the so-called
"freedom of speech," it never mentioned the right to existence,
the right to development, the right to education, the right to
being free from want and the right of not being subject to racial
discrimination, in a vicious attempt to incite a few foreign
trouble-makers in destabilizing their countries and to conquer
these countries "by default."
</P>
<P>
After the end of the Cold War, the United States, instead of
giving up the Cold-War mentality, deemed that chance had come for
it to dominate the whole world, and openly advocated for the
establishment of a unipolar world, with itself as the sole
dominator and the Western value the sole value.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, "protection of human rights" has
become a tool in the hands of the United States to build such a
world and a synonym of the U.S. value. And, whoever refuses to act
in accordance with its value will simply be blamed for "violating
human rights" or creating "humanitarian disasters."
</P>
<P>
The fallacy has already posed a serious threat to world peace.
Respect of sovereignty and territorial integrity of other
countries and non-interference in their internal affairs are the
basic principles of modern international law and also an important
guarantee for world peace.
</P>
<P>
The advocating of the fallacy amounts to a denial of the
concept of state sovereignty as the corner stone of modern
international law and a violation of the United Nations Charter
and all existing international laws.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO's indiscriminate bombing of Yugoslavia has
proven to be a "major experiment" for this fallacy, and also a
precedent that can be followed in large scale in the next century.
</P>
<P>
However, lies can never cover up bloody facts. An increasing
number of people are clearly seeing the nature of the fallacy and
solemnly condemning the heinous crimes committed by U.S.-led NATO
in Yugoslavia. As a Chinese saying goes: "He who is unjust is
doomed to destruction." The United States will never achieve its
ambition for hegemony and for building a unipolar world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
