<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Metallurgical Industry Enhances Energy Conservation Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China's metallurgical industry
aims to reduce the energy consumption required to produce one ton
of iron and steel to 1.23 tons of standard coal this year,
according to a report released by the State Administration of
Metallurgical Industry (SAMI) here today.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the sector saved six million tons of standard coal
valued at 3.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The average amount of standard coal used to produce one ton of
iron and steel dropped to 1.29 tons in 1998, down 58 kg. from the
1997 level.
</P>
<P>
Experts noted that China's metallurgical industry consumes
substantially more energy than its foreign counterparts. For
example, the average amount of standard coal needed to produce one
ton of iron and steel was 245 tons more than that used in Japan
last year.
</P>
<P>
They cited the main reasons as the lower quality of energy and
raw materials used by the sector, as well as the lack of advanced
energy conservation technology.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, the industry will work diligently to
fulfill its long-term target of reducing energy consumption
required to produce a single ton of iron and steel to one ton of
standard coal by the year 2003.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
