<HEADLINE> Indian Air Force Continues to Strike Kargil Sector, Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Air Force (IAF)
Wednesday afternoon continued its air strikes in Kargil sector of
Kashmir where alleged Pakistan-backed infiltrators have occupied
ridges at 16,000 to 17,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
"The strikes have been very effective and they will continue,"
Air Commodore Subhash Bhojwani told newsmen at a special briefing
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At present, "the camps of heavily-armed militants comprising
Pakistan army regulars and Afghan mercenaries have been hit by the
air force mainly in the Drass sub-sector of Kargil," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the start of operations and they would continue till
our defense forces reoccupy our territory," an official statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Over 160 militants have already been killed and a large number
injured in the army operations which began on May 14. The
casualties on the Indian side include 17 killed, 14 missing and 90
injured, the official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the air force operations was to help the army get
the infiltrators out of the Indian territory and allow no
interference from across the border, Air Commodore Bhojwani said.
</P>
<P>
There had been no combat between Indian and Pakistan armed
forces so far, he further said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Wednesday was reported to have vowed to retaliate
against the Indian aerial strikes on "unmanned" areas at the Line
of Control in the Kargil sector of Kashmir and dismissed India's
assertion that Pakistan was pushing in militants into Indian
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
