<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Research Bodies Face Shake Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China is to reshape its research
institutions in a major shake up which will involve a total of 242
scientific bodies attached to China's 10 administrations directly
transferring to industrial enterprises, becoming independent
ventures or science and technology development related match-
makers.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 5,100 independent research institutions
registered in China but one third of them are basically redundant.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, vice-minister of Science and Technology, said here
today at a forum focusing on this significant reform that the
restructuring work is scheduled to be completed by the end of this
June.
</P>
<P>
He said the reform of these research institutions is expected
to become a major breakthrough in China's overall reform of the
sector and will greatly encourage the development of inventions.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhigang, vice-minister of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, explained that of the 242 research organs led by his
commission, 131 will become a part of big enterprises or
industrial groups, 40 will become independent ventures and 18 will
become science and technology development intermediary organs. The
rest will be become a part of universities or dismantled.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the research bodies are involved in ten industries
including coal, metallurgy, nonferrous metals, petro-chemicals,
building materials, machinery, light industry and textiles.
</P>
<P>
He said the reform will help improve the market competitiveness
of the country's industrial enterprises and speed up China's
development of high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
The restructured research organs in enterprises will be allowed
such preferential policies as exemption from income tax, sales tax
and some other kinds of taxes apart from receiving their original
government financial subsidies in the coming five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
