<HEADLINE> World Bank Grants Loans to Aid China's Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank's Board of Executive
Directors approved two loans today to increase the incomes of poor
farmers and boost agricultural production in China, according to
sources from the WB's resident mission in China.
</P>
<P>
The board approved an 80 million U.S. dollars IBRD loan and a
20 million U.S. dollars IDA credit for the Guanzhong Irrigation
Improvement Project, and a 100 million U.S. dollars IBRD loan and
50 million U.S. dollars IDA credit for the Second Loess Plateau
Watershed Rehabilitation Project.
</P>
<P>
The Guanzhong Irrigation Improvement Project aims to increase
grain production in nine irrigation areas, increase the incomes of
farmers and strengthen irrigation management in the Guanzhong
Plain in the Weishui River Valley of Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the Second Loess Plateau Watershed
Rehabilitation Project is to help achieve sustainable development
by increasing agricultural production and incomes, and improving
ecological conditions in tributary watersheds of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The IBRD loan has a maturity of 20 years, including a five-year
grace period, while the IDA credit has a maturity of 35 years.
enditem
