<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Endangered Birds Reproducing In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A pair of ibises, an endangered bird
species, recently built a nest on a mountain slope in Xixiang
County in northwest China's Shaanxi Province, where they laid two
eggs.
</P>
<P>
They are the first ibises to settle on Bashan Mountain on the
Sichuan-Shaanxi border.
</P>
<P>
Liu Gaoming, who works at a nearby nature reserve, reported the
event to the provincial ibis observation center which sent people
to monitor it.
</P>
<P>
The ibis population in China has grown from a mere 7 in 1981 to
the present 136, as a result of environmental protection measures.
</P>
<P>
There used to be large flocks in most of China, Japan, and
Germany, but today the species is found only in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
