<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Improve Irrigation System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Agriculture Secretary
Edgardo Angara Wednesday disclosed that his top priority is to
improve the country's irrigation system to enhance crop output.
</P>
<P>
Angara, a former senator who took his oath as secretary of
agriculture Tuesday, said he plans to build more irrigation
canals and repair existing ones, which are vital in improving
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture plays a vital role in the economy, accounting for
20 to 25 percent of the gross domestic product, or the total goods
and services produced in the country.
</P>
<P>
Angara said that President Joseph Estrada has already issued a
directive to the Department of Budget and Management that the
Department of Agriculture should get the second highest budgetary
appropriation for next year, second only to the Department of
Education, Culture and Sports.
</P>
<P>
The new agriculture chief also promised to prioritize
assistance to Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"The whole of Mindanao can be our food basket," he said.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the National Statistical Coordination Board showed
that from 1990 to 1996, Mindanao produced about 75 percent of the
country's total coconut output, around 68 percent of corn, some 78
percent of banana, and 54 percent of rice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
