<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Launches Three Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- India Wednesday launched three
satellites in its southern part of launching center, official
sources said here.
</P>
<P>
The three satellites include an Indian remote sensing
satellite, a South Korean satellite and a German scientific
satellite. This is the first time for India to launch three
satellites by a single vehicle.
</P>
<P>
The Indian 1,050-kg ocean satellite was placed in a
sun-synchronous polar orbit at a height of about 730 km after
about 18 minutes after it was blasted off at 11:52 local time.
South Korea's 107-kg Kitsat followed 50 seconds later and
Germany's 45-kg Tubsat another 50 seconds later, marking the first
launch of foreign satellites from the Indian soil, the sources
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
