<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libyan Leader Urges S. African Moslems to Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Muammar Gadaffi
has appealed to Moslems in South Africa not to boycott the
upcoming elections in the country, South African Press Association
(SAPA) reported from Libya Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to make an appeal to my brother Moslems to take
part in the election and support the African National Congress
(ANC)," Gadaffi said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Gadaffi's call came at a meeting with a top-level South African
 government delegation which held in a desert location, a
45-minute drive away from the town of Sirte -- 450 kilometers
south of the Libyan capital of Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
Gadaffi said he was speaking in his capacity as the leader of
the World Islamic Peoples Command and as Moslem Imam.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was represented at the meeting by Deputy Minister
of Foreign Affairs Aziz Pahad, Minister of Mineral and Energy
Affairs Penuell Maduna and President Nelson Mandela's
director-general, Jakes Gerwel.
</P>
<P>
Gerwel said Mandela had not appealed to Gadaffi to make the
call, saying that the Libyan leader had possibly read about the
boycott call in news reports.
</P>
<P>
Gadaffi said there were good prospects for a strong
relationship between South Africa and Libya.
</P>
<P>
He praised Mandela's role in ensuring solution of the Lockerbie
dispute and also praised Gerwel and the South Africa's ruling
party ANC.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Maduna said that South Africa was interested in buying
oil from Libya if the price was right.
</P>
<P>
"If they give us a good deal we'll lift it," he told SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Maduna said South Africa currently obtained about 45 percent of
its oil from Iran and 30 percent from Saudi Arabia, with the
balance coming from a variety of sources including its own
synthetic fuels industry.
</P>
<P>
Libyan oil is of good quality, and meets South Africa's
industry specifications.
</P>
<P>
South African energy companies are hoping for a stake in
several large petro-chemical deals in Libya, and several of them
are confident of signing the deals soon.
</P>
<P>
Maduna told Gadaffi that South Africa was more than satisfied
with the business discussions.
</P>
<P>
Gadaffi said he was committed to unifying the African continent
as a whole, hoping this day will come soon.
</P>
<P>
In his talks with South African business executives in Sirte on
the same day, the Libyan leader predicted a thawing of relations
between his country and the United States, now that the issue of
handing over the two men suspected of the 1988 Lockerbie bombing
of a Pan Am flight had been resolved.
</P>
<P>
"They have no reason to delay the resumption of relations
between the two countries now that the problem has been resolved,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Gadaffi laughed at a report that he had personally ordered the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
"I don't care about it. We don't deal with the media, we deal
with ministers and governments."
</P>
<P>
Gadaffi said Libya had suffered under sanctions for the case to
be resolved in the manner that it eventually had been. 
</P>
</TEXT>
