<HEADLINE> Philippine Transport Board Urges Workers Not to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Land Transportation, Franchising
and Regulatory Board (LTFRB) of the Philippines Wednesday appealed
to members of transport groups who announced their plans to
participate in a nationwide strike to reconsider their decision.
</P>
<P>
LTFRB Chairman Dante Lantin said millions of commuters all over
the country will be the ones hurt by the strike, not the three oil
firms they want to send a strong message of protest to.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, various labor and transport groups in Metro Manila
announced that they will stage a transport strike on May 27 to
dramatize their protest against increase in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The striking transport groups can demonstrate their strong
opposition and resentment against the recent oil price increases
by peaceful and orderly means other than making their own
countrymen suffer, Lantin said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the LTFRB assigned fixed routes of buses just in
case there will be a strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
