<HEADLINE> China to Deal with Light Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China's construction department is
drafting laws and regulations on the design, installation and use
of glass walls in a bid to reduce the light pollution caused by
reflection.
</P>
<P>
Since China initiated the reform and opening up drive in 1979,
attractive glass walls have been rapidly spread to most of the
inland cities from coastal cities including Guangzhou and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary statistics show that China has more than 1.7
million square meters of glass walls in use, and the number is
still soaring up.
</P>
<P>
The light pollution produced by concentration, reflection and
refraction because of glass walls has drawn attention from both
experts and residents.
</P>
<P>
Light pollution not only makes people's head swim, but can also
directly causes frequent traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
Construction experts said that the reflection coefficient of
glass walls in summer can reach 80 percent, ten times more than
that of the walls covered by coating and ceramic tiles.
</P>
<P>
Environmental officials here said that the glass wall has been
widely applied in construction but the management of its use has
not be very effective.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that light pollution cannot be eliminated with
current technology and could only be prevented through strict
control of the use of glass walls.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Government turned down nearly 30 designs
of glass walls last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
