<HEADLINE> Ugandan Depositors Swamp Bank to Withdraw Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of panic depositors
swamped Housing Finance Company of Uganda Limited Tuesday to
withdraw massively from the bank which was rumored to be closed
down very soon.
</P>
<P>
The clients filled up the hall at the bank's headquarters on
Kampala road at the Entebbe Road junction and crippled normal
operations half-way through the day.
</P>
<P>
Customers withdrew a total of 250 million shillings (200,000
U.S. dollars) from the bank on that day alone, Wednesday's Monitor
daily quoted the bank manager Sam Rutega as saying that the rumor
started Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Uganda Spokesman Walugembe Musoke later Tuesday
dismissed the panic of withdrawal, saying that the bank was too
viable to go under.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the Treasury and Permanent Secretary of the
Finance Ministry Tumusiime Mutebile also refuted rumors that the
bank was about to be closed, adding that everything there was safe
and sound.
</P>
<P>
The rush was well-grounded because the Bank of Uganda, the
country's central bank, had closed two big commercial banks so far
this year and five banks within 10 months. The visibly volatile
financial sector gives rise to public worries about the safety of
their hard-earned money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
