<HEADLINE> China to Set up Food Supply Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Safety checks on food sources and
supply have been listed as one of the priority projects for
China's "Agenda 21 Agriculture Action Plan" and authorities assess
that introducing such systems will require an investment of 15
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The procedures will include setting up an information network,
an early warning system and a comprehensive analysis of available
foodstuffs, according to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
China is a big food producer and consumer and feeding its 1.2
billion population is a major issue which affects the country as a
whole, and indeed the whole world, said an expert of the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Considering that analysts believe the population will reach 1.3
billion by the end of this century, protecting and maintaining the
safety of food sources is of the utmost importance, according to
the expert.
</P>
<P>
The new procedures, already in the planning stage, will enable
the ministry to carry out short-, medium- and long-term food
supply forecasts, establish a proper agriculture policy and plan
for optimizing food sources through the collection, processing,
analysis and feed back of food production and marketing
information.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
