<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Largest Natural Forest Needs More Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have called for the
setting up of a preservation zone in the Houdingshan Mountains in
northeast Beijing to protect the water quality of the Miyun
Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
Writing in a recent scientific report, experts said that the
establishment of a nature reserve will help ensure the quality of
one of Beijing's major drinking water sources as well as the
precious primeval forest and its bio-diversity.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Beijing University of Forestry and the
Institute of Botany under the Chinese Academy of Sciences carried
out a thorough investigation in the Houdingshan Mountain area, one
of the largest natural forest locations in Beijing Municipality,
last year.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that protecting the forest will also benefit
Beijing's environment and help keep the ecological balance.
</P>
<P>
The forest in Huairou County, 150 kilometers from the urban
area, covers more than 300 square kilometers, 89 percent of the
Houdingshan Mountain.
</P>
<P>
The forest is home to many precious animals and plants which
are under state protection. Experts say it has a wide diversity of
animal species and is an important water source on the upper
reaches of the Miyun Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
The scientists warn that 14 species of plants in the forest are
on the brink of extinction while a further 36 species are in
imminent danger of dying out. Indeed, they say, 12 species which
were existing only thirty years ago when the last survey was
carried out could not be found this time.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say if there is no further protection given to the
forest, the plants, animals and the ecology and environment will
all be endangered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
