<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Redoubles Efforts to Protect Tibetan Antelope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Wildlife protection officials today
burned 361 Tibetan antelope furs which had been confiscated from
poachers in this capital city of northwest China's Qinghai
Province.
</P>
<P>
"The move indicates the determination of the Chinese government
to combat the poaching and smuggling of such pelts," said Zhang
Jianlong from the Wildlife Protection Department under the State
Forestry Administration.
</P>
<P>
"We destroyed the furs because if they were somehow returned to
the market it would encourage rather than discourage poachers," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan antelope is an endangered species and is top of
China's protected species list. It is native to the grasslands in
and around Qinghai Province, Xinjiang Uygur and Tibetan Autonomous
Regions and normally lives up in the mountains between 3,700 and 5,
500 meters high.
</P>
<P>
The animal's fur, known as the "king of wool", has been sold
illegally around the world since early 1990. Shawls, called
shahtoosh, made of such wool can sell for as much as 11,000 U.S.
dollars each on the world market.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, poachers are keen to kill these antelopes because
of the huge financial returns which has led to a drastic decline
in their numbers almost to the verge of extinction.
</P>
<P>
According to wildlife experts the number of Tibetan antelopes
has fallen from 50,000-75,000 in 1995 to the present 30,000. In
the past ten years Chinese police and forest rangers have solved
over 100 cases of smuggling, confiscating 17,000 furs.
</P>
<P>
The state has set up many reserves in an attempt to protect the
Tibetan antelope and launched a series of campaigns against
poachers in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
The latest is jointly organized by the State Forestry
Administration, Qinghai Province and the Xinjiang Uygur and Tibet
Autonomous Regions at the Hoh Xil Nature Reserve, which is located
on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau. It is home to more than 20 rare
animal species such as the Yak and Tibetan antelope.
</P>
<P>
The effort is hugely successful and has resulted in the capture
of thirteen gangs of poachers and the confiscation of 388 Tibetan
antelope pelts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
