<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disabled Chinese to Cross Desert by Wheelchair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A crippled Chinese man has just
left here for northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region
to make an attempt at crossing the Taklimakan Desert, the world's
second largest desert, by wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
Yin Xiaoxing, 29, is expected to start his epic journey across
the 340,000 sq km desert, dubbed "the sea of death", in Xinjiang
by the end of this month and plans to travel some 500 km across it
alone.
</P>
<P>
The man, born into a rural family in east China's Jiangsu
Province, has been confined to a wheelchair since childhood. He is
now less than one meter in height and weighs only 41 kg.
</P>
<P>
"I'm disabled which is a fact I can't change, but I try to live
as a normal person," Yin said.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, Yin began to challenge his disability by traveling
widely across the country, and has since covered more than 57,000
km, including climbing 17 mountains.
</P>
<P>
He set himself the goal of traversing the Taklimakan in 1996
and has been making preparations in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
Yin has chosen to cross Taklimakan in summer because the
natural conditions in the desert become extremely difficult in
this season, with its temperature climbing to as high as 70
degrees centigrade during the day and dropping to 30 degrees below
zero centigrade at night.
</P>
<P>
"I have seven years of traveling by wheelchair, and I'm ready
to face any difficulties ahead," Yin said.
</P>
<P>
The Zhejiang Disabled Persons' Federation and the Zhejiang
Tingdeshuai Clothing Company have donated spare tires, sleeping
bags, cotton-padded clothes and other goods necessary for desert
travel.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Disabled Persons' Federation will also provide him
food and fresh water.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 06:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Hits Southwest Cyprus, Causing Minor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 5.0 on the
Richter scale shook Cyprus at 20:15 (17:15 GMT) Tuesday night, but
causing no serious injuries or severe structural damage, police
said.
</P>
<P>
A Geological Department announcement released Wednesday morning
said that the epicenter was in the Mediterranean Sea, 10
kilometers southwest of the coastal town of Paphos, at a depth of
30 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
In Paphos and Limassol, the island's most earthquake-prone
areas, the tremor was strongly felt, especially in high buildings,
and cracks have appeared in the walls of some homes, police said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has frequently suffered earthquakes which have caused
serious damage and dozens of casualties in previous years.
</P>
</TEXT>
