<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ's Protests Likely if US Imposes Trade Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand may protest to the
World Trade Organization (WTO) if the United States bows to its
protectionist farm lobby and erects barriers to lamb imports, the
Dominion Wednesday quoted New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper reported that Shipley also
appears to leave open the possibility of telephoning U.S.
President Bill Clinton next week about the escalating trade
dispute between New Zealand and the United States.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the United States International Trade
Commission (ITC) has recommended a range of measures to "protect
the U.S. sheep meat industry", including a tariff of around 20
percent on all lamb imports and a quantitative restriction.
President Clinton will decide by the end of next week on the ITC
proposal for tariffs to be used against New Zealand and Australia,
which supply most of the United States' lamb imports.
</P>
<P>
Recently Meat NZ Chairman John Acland returned from Washington
fearful that Clinton may approve the ITC measures to impose
tariffs on New Zealand and Australian lamb.
</P>
<P>
After receiving Meat NZ Chairman Acland in her Beehive office
Tuesday, Shipley threatened to take the United States to the WTO
if President Clinton's ruling is unfavorable to New Zealand trade,
the Dominion said.
</P>
<P>
"It is most certainly an option that's available to our
country. I can tell you that the work has been done. Obviously
though we don't want to pre-empt their decision," Shipley told the
paper.
</P>
<P>
She added that New Zealand is going to defend its right to
trade freely.
</P>
<P>
The United States imported a record 31.6 million kilograms of
lamb in 1998, up from just 18 million kilograms in 1993. New
Zealand earns about 120 million NZ dollars (66 million U.S.
dollars) from its share of the trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
