<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Slides Down Info-League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's ability to compete
in the new information economy is slipping behind its trading
competitors.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Herald, a newspaper published in the country's
biggest city of Auckland, reported Tuesday that New Zealand ranked
 the ninth in 1997, but slipped to the 13th last year, according
to the Information Society Index of the International Data
Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
The index takes into account 23 variables, including social
factors, information infrastructure, computer infrastructure and
Internet connections and usage, to measure how a country or a
region is placed to access, absorb and effectively take advantage
of information and information technology.
</P>
<P>
IDC country manager Dinesh Kumar was quoted as saying that
while New Zealand was still growing, "other countries grew faster
than we did, so we slid down the scale." That slide is expected
to continue, with New Zealand languishing at 19 by 2002, according
to him.
</P>
<P>
Top of the chart in 1998 was the United States, followed by
Sweden, Finland, Singapore, Norway, Denmark, the Netherlands,
Australia, Japan, Canada, Switzerland and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Kumar said New Zealand was dragged down by a poor score in
information infrastructure category, which measures things like
telephone, fax and television ownership, telephone prices, cable
subscriptions and the number of fault calls on the telephone
networks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
