<HEADLINE> Vietnam Launches No-Smoking Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Ministry of Health, in
coordination with the Swedish International Development Agency
(SIDA), launched in Hanoi Tuesday a National No-Smoking Week from
May 25 to 31, local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It has been a traditional no-smoking campaign in Vietnam since
1997.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the campaign is to promote no-smoking habit among
people, especially youth and teenagers, in the interest of the
individuals themselves as well as of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Health calls for concrete rules on the
habit, such as an official ban on smoking in public places.
</P>
<P>
With half of its male population and 3.4 percent of females
smoking, Vietnam ranks the 22nd in the world in this term, smoking
up 5,834 billion Vietnamese dong (roughly 416 million U.S.
dollars) worth of cigarettes in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's armymen, police, youth and teenagers in rural areas
or urban unemployed youngsters are found among the heavy smokers.
</P>
</TEXT>
