<HEADLINE> UAE Newspaper Urges for Stronger GCC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A newspaper in the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) Wednesday urged Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC)
countries to speed up the process of integration and make
the regional alliance stronger.
</P>
<P>
To achieve full GCC integration, much needs to be done on the
national level, said the English daily Gulf News.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial marking the 18th anniversary of the creation of
the GCC on May 25, 1981, the paper urged the six member countries
- Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain, Oman and the UAE - to "take
the next step" to achieve its wider goals.
</P>
<P>
While praising the alliance as the only functioning regional
organization in the Arab world which has made well-known
achievements, the editorial said "it has yet to achieve its full
potential."
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that in some cases, member states' national
interests have prevailed over those of the region. As a
result, "the process of integration seems to be moving in the
opposite direction," it added.
</P>
<P>
"Whether it is the issue of Kuwaiti prisoners in Iraq, the
integration of Iraq into the Arab world, the establishment of a
mutual defense or the adoption of a unified tariff, the states
have been more eager to overlook the greater regional benefits
than to act in unison," the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
It did not mention the UAE's conflict with Iran over the
sovereignty of three Gulf islands. The UAE, which calls for united
actions among GCC states, has been uneasy over recent efforts made
by Saudi Arabia and some other GCC states to improve relations
with Iran, regardless of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
"What needs to be done is for each state to recognize that
there is need for a stronger GCC, even if it means compromise on
some of their national objectives," the paper stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Press Freedoms Unmasked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The so-called freedom of the press
that is advocated by the United States is just hypocrisy,
according to teachers and students at the Journalism School of
People's University of China.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zheng, an associate professor at the journalism school,
told a forum that Chinese students used to have a kind of worship
of press freedoms in the United States, and thought that American-
style press freedoms represented purity and should be followed.
</P>
<P>
But the NATO attack on the Yugoslav Television Station and the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade completely dispelled this illusion and
showed them the true face of American-style press freedoms that
means the American privilege to dominate global publicity, Zhang
said.
</P>
<P>
Yao Lili, who will soon graduate from the journalism school,
said that they used to have a fancy for the Western media, but the
missiles fired by NATO and the blood of the Chinese martyrs helped
them see more clearly the hypocrisy of the U.S. press freedoms
that serve political groups and bang the drum for power politics
and unjust wars.
</P>
<P>
According to Cheng Mei, another professor, the press freedoms
of the United States, characterized by a double standard, have
always been used to serve hegemonism, fabricate lies wantonly,
spread rumors and carry out subversive activities. If you report
the facts you will be accused of destroying the press freedom and
get killed.
</P>
<P>
Professor Guo Qingguang, who is head of the journalism school,
said the U.S. practices hegemonism through invasions, economic
sanctions, and more importantly, by news reports and culture that
help stir up contradictions among people of different ethnic
groups, start internal feuds and cause political chaos. He blames
the NATO attack on Yugoslav Television Station and the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade on the U.S.'s fear of the voice of justice.
</P>
<P>
On the night of May 7, NATO fired missiles from different
directions into the Chinese embassy in Belgrade, killing three
journalists instantly, injuring 20 others and destroying the
building.
</P>
<P>
In a recent letter of protest to the U.S. Embassy in Beijing,
the students of the journalism school said that the United States
had removed the deceptive mask of freedom of the press and had
shown the true face of a hegemony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0216 </DOCNO>
