<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Further Invest in Infrastructure: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) said here
Wednesday that over the next five years the SAR will continue to
invest in infrastructure development estimated at 30 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the Third Ministers' Forum
on Infrastructure Development in the Asia-Pacific Region, Tung
said that this figure is 50 percent higher than what Hong Kong has
spent on its new international airport at Chek Lap Kok and the
associated development.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that Hong Kong has in the past years invested
substantially in infrastructure development. The SAR continues to
find ways to accommodate population growth and relieve urban
congestion, he added.
</P>
<P>
The new airport, which was completed and opened last year, has
been named one of the Top Ten Construction Achievements of the 20
th century at a recent international construction trade show, Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
It will enable Hong Kong to handle passengers and cargoes more
than double the volume at the old airport in a more efficient
manner, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that with the arrival of the digital era, digital
technology will open up new possibilities and offers tremendous
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"We will position ourselves as a leading city in the world for
the development of information technology," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"In pursuit of this vision, we will embark on the development
of a Cyberport in partnership with the private sector," he added.
</P>
<P>
It will provide facilities to attract a strategic cluster of
companies engaged in leading-edge information technology and
services.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that this development will help create the synergies
required to turn Hong Kong into an international multi-media and
information service center and link up our vast hinterland with
the rest of the Region through state of the art communication
networks," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Another response the SAR will make to the challenges of the 21
st century is to make Hong Kong an innovation-led, technology-
intensive economy.
</P>
<P>
"We will broaden and upgrade our economic base by actively
encouraging high value-added and high productivity activities,"
Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The realization of this new vision calls for investment in
technological infrastructure, which is the technological support
given to industrial production and distribution activities through
research and the transfer of research results.
</P>
<P>
Addressing some 70 delegates from 14 members of the forum, Tung
called for more bilateral and multilateral communication and co-
operation in the region.
</P>
<P>
The first Ministers' Forum on Infrastructure Development in the
Asia-Pacific Region was held in 1995 in Osaka, Japan, and the
second in 1997 in Santiago, Chile. The current one will last till
May 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
