<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 05:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Omanis Prefer Local Goods: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Consumers of Oman overwhelmingly
prefer locally-manufactured products, the Dubai-based Khaleej
Times daily reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 62 percent of people in the country, both nationals
and expatriates, opt for "Made in Oman" goods, the paper said,
quoting results of a country-wide survey made by the Omani
Ministry of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
"There exists a significant positive momentum in favor of Omani
products which the local manufacturers can effectively utilize,"
the survey report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The study also revealed that a campaign launched by the
ministry to promote local products has had a significant impact
on creating consumer awareness about goods manufactured in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive survey covered consumers, dealers and
manufacturers, and involved 27 durable and non-durable items
produced in the country.
</P>
<P>
46 percent of the consumers surveyed gave high rating for Omani
products for their quality. While 36 percent felt the quality was
on par with imported items, 18 percent said it was inferior to
foreign brands.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that 76 percent of the population is aware of
locally produced goods.
</P>
<P>
Like other Gulf countries, Oman has been trying to develop
manufacturing industry in recent years as part of its effort to
diversify the national economy, which depends much on oil export.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
