<HEADLINE> Interview: Nepal to Lay More Stress on Ties With India, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Prime minister designate of Nepal
Krishna Prasad Bhattarai said Wednesday that his new government
will lay more stress on relations with India and China.
</P>
<P>
"There shall be no change in the foreign policies that have
been pursued for ages in our country, but there will be only
difference on putting the stress on the issue of our friendship
with our two immediate neighbors, namely India and China," he told
Xinhua in an interview at his residence in Lalitpur, which
neighbors Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
"Stress shall be more on these countries than other neighbors,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali Congress, to which Bhattarai belongs, is poised to
form the next government as it has won a majority of 110 seats in
the elections to the 205-member House of Representatives held on
May 3 and May 17. Party President and Prime Minister Girija Prasad
Koirala has offered the post-poll premiership to Bhattarai, a
senior leader of the party.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai said that he shall assume the top executive post on
Friday or Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said that in further boosting ties with China, there will be
more visits to China, more cultural and student exchanges between
Nepal and China and more publicity about each other in favor of
friendship in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
The septuagenarian leader described both India and China as
very great countries with great cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
"For the last thousand years, we have been keeping very good
relationship with both countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
But since Nepal and India have the same religion, thousands of
the Nepalese people go to India for pilgrimage and millions of
Nepalese nationals are employed there, "naturally our relationship
with them, compared to China, are deeper," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the 11th summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) scheduled for November in Kathmandu, Bhattarai
pledged to do everything possible to ensure a "very pleasant and
comfortable" stay in Nepal for the heads of state or government
from Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
He said Nepal will make the summit "an important question" and
cultivate deeper relations with the other SAARC member states.
</P>
<P>
On his priorities in the national front, the prime minister
designate put poverty eradication as his top priority followed by
education and creation of jobs for the youth. He said it is a very
difficult task.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank listed Nepal as one of the 25 least developed
countries in the world while the Asian Development Bank put the
level of poverty in the kingdom at 42-50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
