<HEADLINE> Utah Beats Portland 88-71 to Avoid Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Karl Malone set the tone early
with another vicious elbow on Brian Grant and the Utah Jazz
avoided elimination and finally displayed the type of poise that
has led them to back-to-back Western Conference titles.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz pulled within 3-2 in their conference semifinal series
with a convincing 88-71 victory over the Portland Trail Blazers
but more importantly watched their less-experienced opponents wilt
under pressure with a chance to close them out.
</P>
<P>
Malone, who sparked the Jazz to a 93-83 victory in Game One
with a left elbow to Grant's jaw, scored 23 points, grabbed eight
rebounds and found the bridge of Grant's nose with an elbow in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Utah jumped out to a 14-4 lead and never trailed in front of a
raucous crowd at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
Game Six is Thursday at Portland, where the Jazz have dropped
nine of their last 11, including Games Two and Three of this
series.
</P>
<P>
Grant, who outplayed Malone in each of the previous three games,
was held to eight points in 39 minutes as Portland lost its cool
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
Mike Dunleavy, the NBA Coach of the Year, went after the
officials after a questionable technical foul was called on Grant.
Dunleavy had to be restrained and eventually was ejected Grant and
Malone had to separated during the fracas.
</P>
<P>
Bryon Russell scored 22 points and John Stockton handed out 14
assists for Utah, which shot a blistering 63 percent in the first
half for a 49-42 lead at the break.
</P>
<P>
Damon Stoudamire drained a jumper to start the second half
before Malone sparked the rout with six straight points, including
consecutive dunks. Jeff Hornacek collected 14 points.
</P>
<P>
Isaiah Rider scored 16 points and Rasheed Wallace had 15 for
Portland, which was held to its lowest point total of the season.
</P>
