<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Funeral Industry Has Enormous Potential (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua)-- The friends of Fan Jiayue are often
shocked when they step into his exhibition hall by the 1.4m. by 1.
1m. black and white photo of him on an electronic screen in what
appears to be a funeral hall, and they puzzle: didn't he just
invite me a few days ago?
</P>
<P>
But they are soon relieved to see that the 52-year-old man is
alive and well, as he explains that this is just his way of
demonstrating his new projector that was designed for use at a
funeral service.
</P>
<P>
Fan is one of just a few people with MBAs among the managers of
China's state-owned enterprises and he has been racking his brains
in search of ways to market products.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition hall and his company headquarters are in a blue
two-story building inside the Beinei Group Corporation compound
within walking distance of the China World Trade Center in eastern
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Since establishing the Beijing Interment and Funeral Facilities
Company in 1993, Fan has been using printed matter and photos to
reach potential customers, mainly funeral homes and officials of
local government divisions that see to it that burials and
funerals are conducted properly. But the fliers got a lukewarm
reception and business moved ahead at a snail's pace.
</P>
<P>
Fan attributes this to the relatively low education level of
people who work at funeral homes, who "prefer to see things that
can impact directly on their eyes."
</P>
<P>
So, he opened the exhibition hall on April 18 and has invited
heads of funeral homes and local government officials to see his
nearly 40 different types of products that range from a plastic
card to ash boxes to gravestones to hearses. Fan's business really
took off.
</P>
<P>
"Once they're here, they instantly see what I'm trying to sell
and they place orders on the spot," he says. Some of the products
have been developed by his company.
</P>
<P>
Fan, also an advisor to the China Interment and Funeral
Association, says that revenues for the past month showed a more
than 3-fold rise over the same period last year. He expects the
company to have sales of more than 7 million yuan this year. Last
year, it sold more than 3 million yuan worth of goods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Funeral Industry Has Enormous Potential (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fan says that he is actively looking for new technology that
can be used in the growing business, because much of it here is
still old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
One example was when he turned to the diminishing numbers of
people who can use writing brushes to write elegant characters for
elegiac couplets and commissioned Qingdao University and Beijing
University to design software that would allow computers to print
out elegiac couplets written in various styles of calligraphy. The
software is now available.
</P>
<P>
Another innovation came when his company started working with
an American company to produce much more cost-effective cremators
than those available in China. The results of this are scheduled
to go on display in November.
</P>
<P>
Fan feels optimistic about his company's prospects, because
every year 7.5 million Chinese die and five million are buried and
2.5 million cremated, meaning a growing demand for services,
equipment, and goods, so "This market will never be weak, it will
be a huge market forever!"
</P>
<P>
China's population is approaching 1.3 billion but there are
only slightly more than 1,300 funeral homes across the country,
most of them using outmoded equipment.
</P>
<P>
The United States has only 250 million people or so but 10,000
funeral homes, Fan says. He has studied the business in about 10
highly developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has a funeral company with profits matching those of
McDonalds," he says enviously, shaking his head in amazement.
</P>
<P>
Civil Affairs Ministry statistics show annual interment and
funeral business in China amounting to more than 20 billion yuan.
But, to put it in a different perspective, this is the same as the
turnover in the commodity market of the city of Yiwu in coastal
Zhejiang Province, one of several big markets in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
