<HEADLINE> World Gas Demand To Grow 2.7 Percent Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- World natural gas demand is
expected to grow at an average annual rate of 2.7 percent to the
year 2010, a senior energy analyst predicted here today.
</P>
<P>
According to Han Dakuang, of the China National Petroleum Corp.
(CNPC) the world's total demand for natural gas will climb to a
little over 3 trillion cubic meters in 2010 from around 2.1
trillion cubic meters in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Demand in the Asia-Pacific region is expected to grow from
around 200 billion cubic meters in 1995 to around 470 billion
cubic meters, he said, with about 6 percent annually growth, well
ahead of the world average.
</P>
<P>
He says that the rapid growth in gas use is the result of
several factors. For a decade, during which time environmental
protection has risen to the top of political agendas, the inherent
cleanliness of gas has been a major factor. But, it is also an
extremely convenient and efficient form of fuel. And the economic
restructuring and urbanization worldwide will sharply increase
demand for gas.
</P>
<P>
In China, Han says, fast economic growth has led to a sharp
increase in demand for gas and he expects the country's demand to
go from the 18 billion cubic meters in 1995 to 100 billion cubic
meters in 2010.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
