<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: History of China's Arctic Expedition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China announced Tuesday that it
will make its first state-sponsored North Pole scientific
expedition from July to September.
</P>
<P>
What follows is a brief history of China's Arctic expedition
work:
</P>
<P>
In 1950, Gao Shiliu, a student at the University of Toronto,
went to the arctic region to do scientific research and the
following year reached the magnetic pole and became the first
Chinese known to have made it to the Arctic region.
</P>
<P>
In 1958, Li Nan, a correspondent of the Xinhua News Agency's
Moscow Branch, made it to the Arctic to interview a group of
Soviet scientists there and was able to reach the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Rebecca Lee Lok-sze, a female Arctic explorer and
travel writer from Hong Kong, successfully reached the North Pole
and planted a Chinese flag there. That same year, with approval
from the Chinese Association of Science and Technology,
preparations began for a Chinese arctic expedition in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, with non-government financial backing, the Chinese
Association set up an Arctic expedition team with help from 25
scientists, journalists, and rear echelon personnel. They left for
the Arctic on March 31 of that year and reached the North Pole on
May 6.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists at the North Pole studied oceanographic, ice,
snow, atmospheric, and environmental phenomena and remote sensing
devices. They also gathered 542 various types of samples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ambassador Rejects U.S. Report on Espionage Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Li Zhaoxing, Chinese ambassador
to the United States, said Tuesday that the purpose of the U.S.
congressional report about so-called China's "theft" of nuclear
secrets is to slander China and derail the bilateral relations
which are important to the peoples of China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The allegations are sheer fabrications out of ulterior
political motives," Li said in a CNN interview.
</P>
<P>
A special U.S. House committee headed by Republican lawmaker
Christopher Cox issued an 872-page report Tuesday, asserting that
China obtained secret information on seven nuclear warheads and
the neutron bomb in "two decades of espionage" at U.S. nuclear
weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
"China does not have any policy of stealing high-tech or any
thing from other countries. China has not stolen anything from the
United States in the field of technology," Li stressed.
</P>
<P>
China, he said, is the country which abides by the spirit of
the charter of the United Nations and the norms of governing
international relations.
</P>
<P>
Some Americans are trying to insult the wisdom and creativeness
of the Chinese scientists and engineers, Li said. "Please don't
underestimate the wisdom of creativeness of the Chinese scientists.
"
</P>
<P>
China has indeed developed its own limited nuclear capability,
the ambassador said, adding that this has been done through self-
reliance and by relying on the efforts and wisdom of the Chinese
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Li said China is a country that loves peace, needs peace and
wants to live in peace with other countries including the United
States.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said
the Cox report was merely a fallacy dreamed up by a few people in
the United States with ulterior motives and in essence an attempt
to stir up anti-China feelings and divert people's attention.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said at a regular press conference that some Americans are
sticking to the Cold War thinking and are making a great effort to
dream up stories about China's spying on U.S. nuclear technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
