<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 80,000 Die of Tobacco-Related Diseases Every Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 80,000 people die of
tobacco-related diseases every year in Bangladesh, The New Nation
daily newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by ADHUNIK, a national anti-tobacco
organization of Bangladesh at a press conference here Tuesday on
the eve of "World No Tobacco Day" on May 31.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco causes 3.5 million deaths across the world each year
and about 10,000 per day, and one million deaths occur only in
developing countries, ADHUNIK's founder president Dr. Nurul Islam
said.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco will become the leading cause of death and disability
by the year 2020 claiming the lives of more than 10 million people
annually in the world, he warned.
</P>
<P>
He narrated the harm of tobacco, and urged the government to
impose enhanced tax on tobacco in the upcoming national budget to
discourage smoking and not to accept any donation from tobacco
manufacturers and producers.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the organization also called on media to play a big
role against tobacco by making the people conscious of the deadly
effects of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
There are about 18 million smokers in Bangladesh spending 10
million take (about 206,000 U.S. dollars) a day buying cigarettes,
and some 60 million people of the country now smoke, ADHUNIK
estimated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
