<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Export Up But Import Down in 1st Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam' export turnover of the first
five months of this year is estimated at 4 billion U.S. dollars, a
2.1 percent year-on-year increase while the import turnover of the
country is to drop by 13 percent against the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Of the figure, according to a report of the Vietnam News
Agency, foreign-invested enterprises registered an export value of
872 million dollars, up by 4.3 percent over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam maintained a high growth rate in the export of crude
oil with more than 6 million tons exported in the five months, a
32.3 percent year-on-year increase. The sector plans to export
14.3 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's rice exports have also been promoted in the past few
months. The country shipped abroad 450,000 tons in May, raising
total rice exports in the first five months of this year to nearly
2 million tons. However, the figure was equal to only 80 percent
of the figure in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
High increases were also posted in the export of other main
items such as sea products (over 300 million dollars) up by 3.8
percent; textile and garments (nearly 540 million dollars) up by
10.5 percent; and footwear (526 million dollars) up by 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Vietnam's cashew nut exports dropped by 43 percent;
groundnuts dropped by 20 percent; and tea dropped by more than 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vietnam imported nearly 4.3 billion dollars worth of
goods, equal to 87 percent of the figure of the same period last
year. Particularly, car imports dropped by more than 50 percent;
clinker by 33 percent; and machinery and equipment, 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports of fertilizer, petrol and oil, materials for plastic
production, cotton and materials for the textile and garment
making, and leather industries in the five months increased
compared with the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
