<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Issue Bonds for Small Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has approved the
issuance of government bonds worth 25 billion baht (675.7 million
U.S. dollars) for small investors starting from June 1, a
Government House press release available Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
The five-year bonds will pay annual interest of 6.75 percent
and be sold for 1,000 baht (27 dollars) each, with a minimum
investment of 10 bonds, or 10,000 baht (270 dollars) per person.
</P>
<P>
Bonds can be transferred and traded in the secondary market,
giving investors flexibility if interest rate conditions change.
</P>
<P>
Priority would be given to retail investors and charity
organizations, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Institutional investors, including financial institutions,
might be able to buy the bonds if available after the subscription
period began.
</P>
<P>
The issue, used to cover the 1999 fiscal deficit, would also
help draw excess liquidity from the money market.
</P>
<P>
Regulators say about 100 billion baht (2.7 billion dollars) in
excess liquidity is in the market, but once the economy picked up,
the funds would be utilized as new loans by financial institutions
to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said earlier that the
government had to be cautious when issuing new bonds to avoid
adversely impacting domestic liquidity in the future.
</P>
<P>
Another 15 billion baht (405.4 million dollars) in bonds could
be issued if the first lot proved successful. The Finance Ministry
was also considering the merits of bond issues for state
enterprises in the local market.
</P>
<P>
Government bonds now trade in the market at 6.4-6.5 percent,
and investors can subscribe to the bonds at the Bank of Thailand,
the Government Savings Bank and their regional branches
nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Traders to Seek Government's Market Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 26 (Xinhua) -- About 600 Thai export companies are
keen to take up an offer of government help to find new markets,
said a Commerce Ministry report, which is available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the government program, the Export Promotion Department
will spend 120 million baht (3.24 million U.S. dollars) on
marketing assistance, the Export-Import Bank will make available
loans totaling 150 million baht (4.05 million dollars) at a
discount rate, and exporters finding new markets can claim double
tax rebates on the costs involved.
</P>
<P>
The five-year assistance program, which is subject to annual
review, was approved by the cabinet shortly after the economic
stimulus package worth 53 billion baht (1.45 billion dollars) was
announced in late March, the report said.
</P>
<P>
All elements of the program are in place, although allowing
double tax rebate claims requires Council of State approval, a
move seen as a formality.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed at boosting revenue from new markets to at
least 50 percent of the country's total export earnings.
</P>
<P>
This could counter any risk of major declines in trade with
Thailand's major partners including the United States, the
European Union and Japan, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Government House press release available
Wednesday, the Thai cabinet has acknowledged that the country's
exports in the first quarter of this year dropped four percent
from the same period last year to 13 billion dollars, while
imports increased 5.8 percent to 11.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
