<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Immense Potential Insurance Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
manufacturing center, has immense potential for the life insurance
business, according to a recent survey that showed that nearly
half its people said they would like to have insurance.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Economic Society queried 10,400 people about their
attitude towards insurance and found that Shanghai residents spent
only 444 yuan per person on insurance last year, which can be
compared with the more than 20,000 yuan per capita in savings, and
this indicates great possibilities for the insurance business.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of people who would like to buy policies is
17.48 percent more than it was in 1997, respondents said they were
dissatisfied with the insurance and services provided by local
insurers. About 56 percent said that they lack characteristic
products and services.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the service most needed include
nursing care coverage for the elderly, accident coverage, and
greater coverage for diseases.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed a lack of knowledge about insurance
among local people, only 4.03 percent of whom knew that the main
function of insurance is not to save money but to provide security.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has some 13 million people and 15 domestic and
overseas-funded insurance companies whose total annual premiums
amounted to 10.3 billion yuan in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
