<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil to Ban Arms Possession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRAZILIA, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso announced here Tuesday a prohibition on arms
sales and eventually a similar prohibition on the possession of
arms, due to the country's growing crime rate.
</P>
<P>
"I am sad to admit that according to United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), Brazil has the
highest rate of crimes committed with firearms," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
Next week the president said he will send an initiative to ban
the sale and possession of arms to congress for approval. Nowadays
all Brazilians are threatened by the use of arms, so the present
situation must be changed, said the president.
</P>
<P>
The initiative requests that individuals turn their firearms
over to any unit of the armed forces, the federal police, or the
civil police. Only personnel of the armed forces, the police,
intelligence organizations, and security companies, which are
registered in accordance with the law, may carry arms.
</P>
<P>
Those who carry weapons illegally will be sentenced to two
years imprisonment, with no right to bail, said Renan Calheiros,
Brazil's justice minister.
</P>
<P>
Those who now possess firearms will have two years to hand them
in, and will receive a lawful indemnity, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to UNESCO, Brazil has the highest murder rate in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Ninety percent of the crimes committed in Rio de Janeiro are
not solved and in San Paulo only 1.9 percent of all crimes are
resolved, said Calheiros.
</P>
<P>
Rio de Janeiro last year reported the sale and registration of
5,444 firearms, while the figure for Sao Paulo was 3,635. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheaper Films More Popular In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Vice-director of the
Changchun Film Studio in northeast China's Jilin Province Han
Zhijun says that the Chinese filming business is still in a slump
and that high costs means high risks, so the studio has turned to
low-cost films to attract audiences.
</P>
<P>
The studio shot "The Election of a Village Head" and three
other films that cost only 1.7 million yuan (200,000 U.S. dollars)
each, but that the low cost does not mean low quality. Many low-
cost films have had good returns.
</P>
<P>
"The Day without a Hero", for example, made by the Beijing
Forbidden City Film Company last year, cost only 3.8 million yuan,
but it got 20 million yuan at the box office and a lot of domestic
prizes.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an Film Studio, which produced "Red Sorghum", has made
many films in recent years, most costing less than 3 million yuan
each, and, the 7 films made by the Shanghai Yongle Film Company
this year are low-budget.
</P>
<P>
But, the cost of Chinese films over the last few years has been
increasing to more than 4 million yuan each, some even costing
hundreds of millions of yuan, but many didn't break even.
</P>
<P>
"A Time to Remember", directed by Ye Daying, the producer of "
Red Cherry", cost over 20 million yuan, but it was a complete
failure and only 3 of the 82 films last year showed a profit.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yimou, the well-known director, says that the Chinese
don't produce films with lots of technology at a high cost and
should focus on taste, content, and reflecting real life.
</P>
<P>
People at Changchun say that a lot of imported low-budget films
like "The Bridges of Madison County" had tremendous box-office
results and that the Chinese film industry should learn from them.
</P>
<P>
Many professionals in the film industry say that low-budget
films are the best way for China to reduce risks in the fickle
business, but the Central Government should support films that are
important like "the Opium War" to ensure quality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
