<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Official Disagrees to House Espionage Case Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson said Tuesday that there is no evidence of wholesale
loss of information in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The (U.S. House) report discusses the possible theft of
neutron technology discovered in 1996. This allegation is based on
one piece of intelligence reporting, and the Federal Bureau of
Investigation has been unable to identify a logical suspect,"
Richardson said when commenting on the so-called espionage case at
a press conference.
</P>
<P>
A special U.S. House committee led by Republican lawmaker Chris
Cox issued the 872-page report Tuesday, alleging that China
obtained secret information on seven nuclear warheads and the
neutron bomb in "two decades of espionage" at U.S. Nuclear weapons
laboratories.
</P>
<P>
"I also want to put this report into proper perspective. This
is no evidence of a wholesale loss of information," Richardson
said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It would be a mistake to attempt to use this report
for political gain."
</P>
<P>
"China is not up to par with the United States on nuclear
development. It is far behind us," the energy secretary said. "
There is no evidence that is changing."
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said
the Cox report was merely a fallacy dreamed up by a few people in
the United States with ulterior motives and in essence an attempt
to stir up anti-China feelings and divert people's attention.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said at a regular press conference that some Americans are
sticking to the Cold War thinking and are making a great effort to
dream up stories about China's spying on U.S. nuclear technology.
</P>
<P>
"Their despicable attempt is doomed to fail," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Inn Cozy Home For Qomolangma Climbers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The inn has no luxury rooms and no
attentive maids, but many Chinese and foreign mountain climbers
think it's great before or after climbing Mt. Qomolangma.
</P>
<P>
The Hahu Inn, a small structure with 23 sparse rooms built out
of earth, in Dingri County in Tibet is well-known among
international mountaineers and people can easily locate the tiny
inn alongside the Sino-Nepalese Road.
</P>
<P>
Nema, the hostess, is always there, busy pouring hot butter-tea
into the cups of guests who are discussing their experience on the
Himalayan peak or in other parts of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
May and June are the high season for mountaineering in the area,
Nema says. The inn is more than 100 kilometers from Mount
Qomolangma. Her family were farmers who opened the tiny guesthouse
nine years ago and she became the manager when her son died. The
family of three now operate it.
</P>
<P>
"I've got used to this kind of life with many guests around,
talking and laughing," she says, "and I feel uneasy and lonely
during winter days when the visitors are scarce." Photos taken by
the climbers are the main decoration in the rooms.
</P>
<P>
Nema says that all guests, no matter where they come from, need
a clean toilet, so Hahu's toilet is the most beautiful place at
the inn.
</P>
<P>
The inn offers Tibetan dishes, or, if the guests are not
accustomed to Tibetan flavors, they can get instant noodles and
mineral water.
</P>
<P>
To many guests' surprise, Nema only charges 10 yuan per night
per person, no matter where they're from.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Cambodia Agree to Solve Border Issues Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam and Cambodia have agreed to
finalize all outstanding border problems before the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
This was reached during the talks between Vietnamese leaders
and visiting Cambodian parliamentary speaker Prince Norodom
Ranariddh who is on an official visit to Vietnam at the invitation
of his Vietnamese counterpart Nong Duc Manh, according to reports
of the local press on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and Cambodia share a common border of about 1,130 km.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai told Ranariddh at a
separate meeting that Cambodia and Vietnam should actively settle
border problems before the 21st century to have a border of peace
and friendship for the younger generations of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Khai asked Ranariddh in his capacity as parliamentary speaker
to facilitate conditions for Vietnamese residents in Cambodia to
live and work in line with Cambodian law as Cambodians enjoy.
</P>
<P>
Khai also told Ranariddh that Vietnam wanted to resume and
develop trade with Cambodia and had nearly completed drawing up a
program on trade cooperation with Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh expressed his thanks to Khai for their support for
Cambodia in becoming an ASEAN member.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the implementation of the agreements signed
between the two countries during Prime Minister Hun Sen's visit to
Vietnam last year, and agreed with an acceleration of negotiations
to reach a border agreement between the two countries before the
new century.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh held talks with Chairman of Vietnam's National
Assembly Nong Duc Manh on Tuesday morning and was also received by
Party General Secretary Le Kha Phieu and President Tran Duc Luong
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He told Phieu that the Cambodian people were eagerly waiting
for the upcoming visit by Phieu and hoped that the visit would
contribute to the strengthening of solidarity, friendship and
comprehensive cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
