<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Telecom's Monopoly Being Challenged (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China Telecom will soon find
stronger competition in telecommunications and my risk losing its
monopoly as more competitors enter the market.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways has sent a strong challenge to China
Telecom. The ministry already has a complete nationwide
telecommunications network, second only to China Telecom,
consisting of 120,000 kilometers of telecommunications lines, 66,
000 kilometers of long-distance telecommunications lines, and 4,
593 kilometers of digital microwave lines.
</P>
<P>
According to Ministry officials, they are planning to establish
a large telecommunications company that will be able to do exactly
what China Telecom does, over these existing networks and
preparations are underway for the "China Railway
Telecommunications and Information Group", with the Ministry and
its administrative bureaus as shareholders.
</P>
<P>
"We have no problems in getting permission and a license from
the State Council, and once approved, the company can provide
comprehensive telecommunications services within 6 to 8 months,
after having improved its networks," says Peng Peng, a ministry
official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom's Monopoly Challenged (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Peng is in charge of preparations work and says that
telecommunication services will become a pillar of the state-owned
railroad industries.
</P>
<P>
He attended the "China Telecommunications Development Forum" in
Beijing on May 15, which was sponsored by the State Development
Commission, to discuss reforms of networks operated by the
railways and how to give them a commercial function.
</P>
<P>
He says that officials agreed with a proposal on how to go
about this at a recent meeting, but that the switchboards on the
railroad network have a capacity of only 1.5 million lines, or one
percent of China Telecom's capacity.
</P>
<P>
But, their switchboards can be increased more than 10-fold.
</P>
<P>
China has only three telecommunications companies -- China
Telecom and the smaller China Unicom and China Jitong, which have
to pay the big brother for the use of its telecommunications
networks.
</P>
<P>
China's railways provide channels for China Unicom's GSM (
global system of mobile phone) system, which is currently the
second largest telecommunications service provider in China.
</P>
<P>
China Jitong is also doing business via the railroad
telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
Market analyst say that money and know-how will not be a big
problem for China's railroad sector to expand telecommunications
quickly and that they can easily become the second largest player
in China's telecommunications business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telecom's Monopoly Challenged (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ministry of Information Industry is also drafting its "
Telecommunications Administration Regulations" and many other
telecommunications networks that were previously used only for
specific purposes will be encouraged to move into commercial areas.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the State Administration of Radio, Film and
Television is making preparations for possible telecommunications
businesses.
</P>
<P>
The cables owned by Beijing cable television departments have
been used for data exchanges and for several internal ministry
networks under the State Council.
</P>
<P>
In April, 1999, the administration announced a plan to
establish the "China Cable Television Networks Corporation", which
is expected to get involved in telecommunications rather than just
the cable business.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission also approved the
China Express Networking Demonstration Project in April, 1999,
which will become another major telecommunications company. It is
jointly funded by the Chinese Academy of Sciences, Ministry of
Railways, State Administration of Radio, Film and Television, and
Shanghai's Municipal Government.
</P>
<P>
The project will provide basic telecommunications services that
are integrated into existing wide-band optical fiber networks
operated by the State Administration of Radio, Film and Television
and Ministry of Railways.
</P>
<P>
The project uses network technology to provide telephone
services, on-line services, and multimedia data transmission.
</P>
</TEXT>
