<HEADLINE> ASEAN Business Forum Opens in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A business forum of Chambers of
Commerce and Industry (CCI) of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) opened here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day business forum is held in conjunction with the 56th
Council Meeting of the ASEAN CCI which was inaugurated Tuesday.
The council meeting is discussing ways and means to overcome the
current economic crisis and to face challenges of the next
millennium.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister of Commerce Major-General Kyaw Than said in
his inaugural address that the world economy has passed through
two phases of development in the last 50 years, warning that it is
now entering the third phase of globalized economy.
</P>
<P>
Globalization, which calls for greater integration and
interlocking economic relationships among national economies and
is a natural outgrowth of technological advances in
communications, transport and access to information, has become an
irreversible process, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"This interconnected economy is transforming the world in more
fundamental ways than is implied by the globalization of goods and
services," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that there are signs of adding a new dimension
to the integration process with the world approaching the end of
the 1990s, adding that rapid advances in digital technologies and
communications networks are creating the possibility of borderless
economy in key sectors.
</P>
<P>
The minister called for further deepening the integration and
cooperation within ASEAN, both in public and private sectors not
just to face the challenges of the borderless globalized economy
only, but also to make best use of the business and investment
opportunities arising out of it in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
The forum highlights promotion of foreign direct investment in
ASEAN countries, investment potentials and opportunities in
Myanmar, small and medium enterprises development in Myanmar and
ASEAN region, and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
There are eight ASEAN CCI member nations -- Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar joined the ASEAN CCI in October 1997 after it became an
ASEAN member earlier in July that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
