<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese City Protecting Old Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The government of Xi'an, one of
China's imperial capitals, recently announced a protection list of
600 old trees, most of them rare species.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-two are more than 1,000 years old and date back to the
Tang (618-907) or even the Han (206 B.C.-220 A.D.) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
A group of botanists, headed by Tian Wenjia, took 10 years to
complete a thorough study of the trees and have set up files that
contain the names, ages, and serial number of each tree and they
have put fences around them and lightning rods on them.
</P>
<P>
According to a city regulation, no one can cut or move them at
will and construction projects will have to find ways to avoid
damaging them.
</P>
<P>
Tian says that the protected trees are valuable for plant
studies, afforestation, environmental protection, and history and
culture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
