<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warmer Weather Drawing Tourists To Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Tourists are coming to China's Tibet
Autonomous Region in larger numbers and earlier than usual because
of its warmer weather and better transportation service and
facilities.
</P>
<P>
According to local analysts, average temperatures on the
plateau have been up half a degree centigrade annually and in 1998
hit a record high of 9 degrees, as a result of which, plants are
turning green earlier and the amount of oxygen in the air is
increasing. The peak tourism period used to run from May to
September, but it now starts in April and ends in November.
</P>
<P>
The length of roads is up to 22,400 kilometers. They link all 7
cities and 73 counties in Tibet and go to the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, and Qinghai, Sichuan, and Yunnan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has 47 travel agencies and 77 hotels that can accommodate
foreigners, with over 8,000 beds. The Regional Tourism
Administration also has offices in Los Angeles and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, last year, Tibet had over 390,
000 tourists, 92,000 of them from overseas, the largest number of
tourists the region has seen since tourism began here 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists went up by 60 percent in the first
quarter of this year, from the same period of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
