<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major Beijing-
based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, met here Tuesday with Edmund Ho Hau Wah, who
has been appointed the first Chief Executive of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Li said that the appointment means that Macao will enter a new
period under the "one country, two systems" and "Macao people
governing Macao" principles and with a high degree of autonomy, as
written in the Basic Law of the Macao SAR.
</P>
<P>
-- China will soon amend the existing Accounting Law and enact
provisional regulations on futures trade management, according to
the 18th Executive Meeting of the State Council held here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, presided over by Premier Zhu Rongji, discussed and
passed in principle a draft amendment to the Accounting Law and a
draft of the Provisional Regulations on the Management of Futures
Trade.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, told Emile
Brou, president of the National Assembly of Cote d'Ivoire that
political stability is the basis for economic development, and the
healthy growth of Cote d'Ivoire's economy can be attributed to its
stable political situation.
</P>
<P>
Brou and a delegation of Cote d'Ivoire's National Assembly
members are now on an official visit to China as guests of Li, who
met the delegation at the Great Hall of the People here yesterday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao expressed his satisfaction
with the smooth development of friendly ties between China and
Cote d'Ivoire during his meeting with Emile Brou.
</P>
<P>
-- President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah of the Republic of Sierra Leone
will pay a state visit to China from May 31 to June 6, at the
