<HEADLINE> Sampras Struggles at French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 25 (Xinhua) -- World number two Pete Sampras on
Tuesday struggled five sets on center court to survive little-
known Costa Rican Juan Antonio Marin in a French Open first round
match.
</P>
<P>
The American second seed, chasing the only Grand Slam to elude
him, won 6-7, 6-4, 7-5, 6-7, 6-4 in four hours and 18 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who went out in the second round last year to
Paraguay's Ramon Delgado, had mostly himself to blame. In a match
peppered with unforced errors and inaccuracies, Sampras looked
rusty in his first major tournament of the season after missing
the Australian Open in January.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other action, Brazilian Gustavo Kuerten, a
potential quarter-final opponent of Sampras, went past Spain's
Galo Blanco with a comfortable 6-4, 6-4, 6-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
Third seed Pat Rafter of Australian came back from one set down
to crush Swiss Roger Federer 5-7, 6-3, 6-0, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Last year's losing finalist Alex Corretja, fellow-Spaniard
Felix Mantilla and Sweden's Thomas Enqvist were the other seeds in
action who made it easily into the next round.
</P>
<P>
In the women's tournament, former French Open champions Steffi
Graf of Germany and American Monica Seles both advanced to the
second round with easy victories.
</P>
<P>
Graf, back in Paris after a one-year break through injury, beat
Bulgarian Magdalena Maleeva 6-2, 6-0 while Seles, a three times
winner between 1990 and 1992, dismissed China's Fang Li 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Local favorite Mary Pierce, a losing finalist in 1994, was also
impressive in her 6-4, 6-3 win over South African Joannette Kruger.
</P>
<P>
American Jennifer Capriati, the youngest semifinalist of a
Grand Slam tournament in Paris in 1990 aged just 14, won her first
match in six years at Roland Garros against Virginia Ruano Pascual
6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Seeded second Davenport also had an easy first round, sweeping
past fellow-American Jane Chi 6-3, 6-1. 
</P>
