<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Protecting Ecology Environment Along Major Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China has a number of environmental
and ecological projects on the middle and upper reaches of the
Yangtze and Zhujiang rivers to help sustained social and economic
development in the areas.
</P>
<P>
A third of China's population and 40 percent of its industries
and agricultural production are in the two river basins. To
maintain the ecological balance on the upper and middle reaches is
important to the development along the lower reaches, where much
of the country's economic power is found in the city of Shanghai
and in Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, the central government began the first phase of the
Yangtze River Protective Forest Project and since then, over 763
million yuan has been spent on 34.88 million hectares of forests.
In 1996, a similar project was begun along the Zhujiang River.
</P>
<P>
To further stop soil erosion, the central government has issued
a ruling on turning mountainside fields with a slope of 25 degrees
or greater, back into forests.
</P>
<P>
Last October, governments in the south moved to ban the logging
of natural forests and some provincial and ethnic autonomous
region officials are expected to meet next month to discuss
further cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poland Sees Foreign Trade Shrinking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Poland's foreign trade fell in the
first quarter of the year with exports dropping to 6.5 billion U.S.
dollars, down by 8.2 percent from the same period last year, while
imports were down by 6.5 percent to 10.4 billion dollars, the
General Statistics Bureau said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The country's total foreign trade deficits in the first quarter
of the year were 3.9 billion dollars, as compared with 4.1 billion
dollars during the same period last year, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The Polish News Agency, however, cited preliminary statistics
by the Central Bank as saying that foreign trade deficits in the
first quarter of 1999 were only 2.9 billion dollars while those of
the same period last year were 3.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The discrepancies stem from the different statistical materials
used by the two organizations. The Central Bank based its
statistics on transferred accounts figures, while the General
Statistics Bureau based its calculations on registered materials
at customs.
</P>
<P>
The statistics authority also said that Poland's current
accounts income deficits rose sharply from 488 million dollars in
February to 844 million dollars in March. The balance of payments
deficits in the first quarter amounted to 2.2 billion dollars
while those at the same period last year were two billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Reports here attributed the worsening foreign trade situation
to its shrinking trade volume with Russia, which has disappeared
from the list of Poland's top 10 trading partners.
</P>
<P>
Poland's exports to Western industrial nations in the first
quarter of the year increased by two percent as compared with that
of last year.
</P>
<P>
The drastic contraction in foreign trade has triggered the fear
that it could lead to a further drop in the country's economic
growth rate. The Polish government has already lowered its gross
domestic product growth target from its originally planned 5.1
percent to 3.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
