<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Batch of 201 Seats Declared in Nepal Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of 201 seats in
the 205-member House of Representatives of Nepal have been
declared by Wednesday. Two breakaway factions suffered a
humiliating rout.
</P>
<P>
The elections, the third in the kingdom since the multi-party
system was restored in 1990, were held on May 3 and May 17.
</P>
<P>
As in the past two elections, the Nepali Congress and the
Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML)
remain the two dominant powers in national politics. The Nepali
Congress clinches 110 seats while the CPN-UML bags 68, the
state-run radio said.
</P>
<P>
The former is prepared to form its majority government while
the latter has expressed its commitment to perform its role as a
constructive opposition in the house.
</P>
<P>
The National Democratic Party (RPP) comes third with 11, the
Nepal Sadbhavana Party and the National People's Front 5 each, and
the Nepal Workers and Peasants Party and the United People's Front
1 each, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of Nepal (Marxist-Leninist, CPN-ML) and the
RPP (Chand), which broke away from the CPN-UML and the RPP
respectively early last year, fail to win even a single seat.
</P>
<P>
And their top leaders, including CPN-ML President Sahana
Pradhan, General Secretary Bam Dev Gautam, RPP (Chand) President
Rajeswor Devkota and parliamentary leader and three-time prime
minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand, all lost.
</P>
<P>
But Gautam has a chance in the No. 1 constituency of Kathmandu,
where elections were rescheduled for June 8 with the capital's No.
3 constituency due to the death of CPN-UML candidate Man Mohan
Adhikari.
</P>
<P>
Elections in the No. 5 constituency of Siraha district and the
No. 3 constituency of Sunsari district were refixed for June 23
and June 26 respectively due to the death of candidates.
</P>
<P>
The elections in the four constituencies will produce the
remaining four seats in the house.
</P>
<P>
Twelve women were elected and 10 of them are new faces. But
none of the 619 independents won. 
</P>
</TEXT>
