<HEADLINE> Inter-Andean Trade Reduces in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Trade among the Andean Community in
1998 stood at 5.33 billion U.S. dollars, down 5.2 percent from
1997, a press report said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Andean Community is made up of Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador,
Peru and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
The countries which registered the highest trade volume in 1998
were Colombia and Venezuela, with almost two billion dollars each,
followed by Peru with 600 million, Ecuador with 400 million and
Bolivia with 250 million.
</P>
<P>
The Inter-Andean trade had registered an annual growth of 6.5
percent to reach 4.7 billion dollars in 1996 and 5.62 billion
dollars in 1997, the report recalled. 
</P>
