<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Province Getting More Overseas Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 26 (Xinhua) -- China's Shandong Province, whose GDP
is third in the country, had 113,800 overseas visitors for the
first four months of this year, up 48 percent from the
corresponding period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Most of them visited the cities of Qingdao and Yantai, two
major coastal tourist spots.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the growth to provincial efforts to boost
the growth of tourism and Shandong has set a goal of making
tourism a major part of it's economy.
</P>
<P>
This year, it has a series of preferential policies for
developing the industry, such as investing in infrastructure,
attracting overseas investment, and providing preferential
treatment to local tourist businesses that issue bonds and stocks.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Shandong received nearly 55 million domestic
tourists and 600,000 overseas tourists, bringing an income of 24.6
billion yuan, or 3.33 percent of it's GDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
