<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sperm Quality Drops Because of Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The sperm quality of Chinese men
has dropped considerably over the past decade and a half,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The quality declined 10 percent in the 16 years from 1981 to
1996, a recent survey result shows.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 healthy Chinese men participated in the
investigation. Three indicators, namely the quantity of sperm
cells, the amount of sperm and the number of living sperm cells,
were analyzed.
</P>
<P>
Findings show that the three indicators have dropped 10.3
percent, 18.6 percent and 10.4 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The survey was recently conducted by a scientific research
institute under the State Family Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Men from 39 cities and counties across China, including Beijing,
Shanghai and Tianjin, took part in the survey.
</P>
<P>
The areas with a higher level of industrialization recorded a
larger drop in the three indicators.
</P>
<P>
The deteriorating environmental condition is to be blamed for
the plunge in sperm quality, researchers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boxing Authority Won't Block Tyson's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Nevada boxing officials said
Tuesday they won't do anything to block Mike Tyson's return to the
ring after the former heavyweight champion's early release from a
Maryland jail yesterday.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that Tyson could make his comeback fight as
early as August 21, with a possible bout in Las Vegas against the
likes of Axel Schulz or Brian Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
"August 21 is certainly a date we're looking at," said Larkin,
who runs boxing for the Showtime network. "Hopefully in the next
couple of days we'll have something concrete."
</P>
<P>
"My feeling is that he has a license," said James Nave, vice
chairman of the Nevada Athletic Commission. "I don't see the need
for a hearing."
</P>
<P>
Larkin said: "We all agreed that while Mike Tyson was in jail,
we wouldn't make any plans for his fights. Now, he's been out only
24 hours and we just haven't gotten to that point yet. But we're
going to start right now."
</P>
<P>
Tyson had his last fight on January 16 with a fifth round
knockout of Francois Botha. Tyson remains one of the biggest pay-
per-view attractions in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
