<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sacramento's Petrie Named NBA Executive of the Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Sacramento Kings vice president
Geoff Petrie, who built a team that made the playoffs for just the
second time in 13 years and threw a scare into the Utah Jazz in
the first round, today was named the 1998-99 NBA Executive of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
Sacramento earned the sixth playoff spot in the Western
Conference this season with a 27-23 record in the lockout-
shortened season. The 27 victories equaled their total of last
season's 82-game schedule.
</P>
<P>
Petire, who is in charge of the coaching and scouting staffs,
team negotiations and player acquisitions, made several bold
offseason moves to improve the team.
</P>
<P>
He acquired forward Chris Webber from Washington for Mitch
Richmond and Otis Thorpe and selected point guard Jason Williams
with the seventh pick in last year's draft.
</P>
<P>
Webber, Williams and Rick Adelman, who was hired as coach in
September, led the Kings into the postseason for the first time
since 1996. They extended the two-time defending Western
Conference champion Jazz to five games in the first round, losing
the decisive fifth contest in overtime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
