<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Deals At Chinese Tea Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Fourth Pu'er Tea Fair held
recently in the city of Simao in Yunnan Province resulted in 250
million yuan worth of deals.
</P>
<P>
The 3-day fair allowed overseas and local business people to
signed agreements that would bring in foreign capital. Most of the
foreign businessmen came from Japan and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The first tea fair was held in 1992. Thanks to the '99 World
Horticultural Exposition that is going on in Kunming, the
provincial capital, this tea fair had a larger number of visitors
than the previous three.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Simao has been a tea trade
center for more than 1,000 years. Recently, local specialists
discovered the world's oldest tea trees in the northern part of
the city, the oldest of which is about 2,700 years old.
</P>
<P>
Simao is the largest tea producer in the province and has 30,
000 hectares of tea plantations with an annual output of nearly 15,
000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
