<HEADLINE> Jazz Try to Stay Alive Against Blazers in Western Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- When the season began, the Utah
Jazz felt it was their time to win the NBA championship. But
tonight is the crucial time for the two-time Western Conference
champions, who must beat the Portland Trail Blazers or head home
for the summer.
</P>
<P>
Utah trails the best-of-seven semifinal series, 3-1, has lost
three straight after a victory in Game One and is on the verge of
its earliest playoff exit since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz advanced to the NBA Finals in each of the previous two
seasons, losing to Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls both times.
</P>
<P>
The Jazz-Blazers encounter is the only conference semifinal
series yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
Utah, which many people considered the favorite to win the NBA
title after Jordan's retirement, appears to have met its match in
an athletic and deep Portland squad.
</P>
<P>
Isaiah Rider scored seven of his 24 points in the final 30
seconds on Sunday as the Blazers continued to perform like playoff
veterans down the stretch while the Jazz have faltered. Portland's
three victories in the series have come by an average of just six
points.
</P>
<P>
If the Jazz can remain alive, Game Six of the series would be
Thursday night in Portland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
