<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said Tuesday that his
administration will continue the policy of engagement with China.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly believe that our continuing engagement with China
has produced benefits for our national security," Clinton said in
a speech in Edinburg Town, Texas State, following a U.S.
congressional report which asserted China obtained nuclear secrets
through "espionage" from the United States. (US-China-Clinton-
Report)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
visiting German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer Tuesday stressed
the "unity" of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization on Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference, Albright and Fischer said
they "see eye-to-eye" on a great deal of issues on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"I think that we really have spent a lot of time talking about
the unity of the alliance, our determination to follow through on
the air campaign and working towards, as I said, preparing for
success," Albright said. (US-Germany-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- Decision-making body of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) on Tuesday approved a revised plan for an
expanded Kosovo ground troops to police law and order after Serbs
withdraw from the southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The NATO's North Atlantic Council will handed over the new plan
to NATO generals for final authorization. Under the plan, an
estimated 50,000-strong force will be sent into Kosovo from the
Republic of Macedonia once Serb forces withdraw from Kosovo on the
basis of a political agreement between the West and the Republic
of Yugoslavia. (NATO-Plan-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
