<HEADLINE> Chinese Prefecture Attracts Foreign Tourists With  Festivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Qiandongnan Prefecture, in
southwest China's Guizhou Province, plans to attract more overseas
visitors with its colorful festivals held mostly by ethnic
minority groups.
</P>
<P>
Yang Bin, a deputy commissioner of the prefecture, told Xinhua
that local people have 135 various festivals, 80 percent of which
are for young people to provide them with an opportunity to meet a
partner.
</P>
<P>
The Guizhou Miao Sister Festival, a sort of Valentine's Day,
the Kaili Lusheng (a traditional musical instrument) Festival, the
Zhenyuan Dragon-Boat Festival, the Shanmu River Drifting Festival,
the Congjiang Orange Festival, and the Rongjiang Water Melon
Festival are some of the most popular.
</P>
<P>
Most festivals are yearly events, but some, like the Miao
Guzang Festival, are held once every 13 years.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, all 16 cities and counties in
Qiandongnan have been opened to overseas tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
