<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decoding Message Of 300 Year-Old Tibetan Music Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A Tibetan scholar has been able to
interpret a collection of 300 classical Tibetan musical works that
were played by imperial musicians 300 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Gengduipeijie, 46, an associate professor in the Art Department
at Tibet University, started his work on decoding the classical
book, which is entitled "Joyful and Bright Festive Banquet".
</P>
<P>
This is the only imperial Tibetan music book known, according
to the Tibetan scholar. The works include preludes, dance tunes,
light music, instrumental music, and epilogues, he explains and
says he is going to put the decoded musical works in computer
files or on a CD.
</P>
<P>
Cebai Jogma, a history teacher at a middle school in Lhasa, the
capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region, says that the musical
works are mostly related to classical stories and religious
matters and that many are cheerful enough that they are a must on
festive occasions.
</P>
<P>
The musical works have been recorded and broadcast by Tibet TV
and some Tibetan musicians are planning on playing the pieces
abroad.
</P>
<P>
In 1688, the Tibetan local government summoned a large group of
Tibetan musicians to work on the musical collection, according to
the teacher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Salamander Found in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A 110-cm giant salamander
weighing 21.5-kg has been found in the capital of China's Henan
Province.
</P>
<P>
The huge amphibian was discovered two months ago by a local
farmer at a market in Xishan County. To protect the rare animal,
Sun Jizhang, the farmer, bought it for the princely sum of 30,000
yuan (3,610 U.S. dollars) and took it home.
</P>
<P>
The timid, gray animal has four small flippers, Sun said, and
sometimes produces a baby-like cry at night.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jiantang, the deputy-director of the city's zoo, says that
the giant salamander is on the list of animals that have state
protection. A salamander of this size is rarely seen in China, he
says, and the zoo will adopt the animal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
