<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law Courses to Focus on Analysis, Reasoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Graduates will no longer specialize
in the study of specific aspects of law - Chinese law schools are
now trying to bring up a new generation of legal practitioners
with a broader understanding of the law in general and a better
grasp of analytical argument, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
"Undergraduate education should help train all-round legal
personnel with a certain depth of knowledge of particular laws,"
the paper quotes Zhao Xianglin, vice-president of China University
of Political Science and Law (CUPL) as saying during an
international conference on legal education for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In a major reform of the curricula of law schools in China last
year, all specialties were abolished with the result that every
student had to study basic courses for all major branches of law,
the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The reform also means more emphasis will be put on practical
programs instead of the former concentration on book knowledge to
enable students to get hands-on experience in the profession.
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference, hosted by CUPL, which began yesterday,
is being attended by nearly 90 law school deans and experts on
legal education from 13 countries and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Police Officer Admits Torturing Haitian Immigrant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 25 (Xinhua) -- After devastating testimony from
fellow police officers, a white police officer in New York
admitted Tuesday to the brutal beating and sexual torture of a
black Haitian immigrant.
</P>
<P>
Justin Volpe, 27, pleaded guilty in his federal trial on civil
rights charges.
</P>
<P>
He admitted sodomizing Albert Louima with a wooden stick in a
police station house bathroom and threatening to kill him if he
tells anyone.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors say the assault took place after Volpe mistakenly
thought Louima, 32, punched him in a disturbance outside a
Brooklyn's nightclub on August 9, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Volpe admitted that he realized later that it was not Louima
who had originally hit him in the face.
</P>
<P>
The incident shocked New York and heightened tensions between
the city's minority community and the police department. It even
has drawn national attention over police brutality.
</P>
<P>
Volpe, son of a retired police detective, faces a maximum
sentence of life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
A sentencing date is to be set after the trial of four other
white police officers accused of violating Louima's civil rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990526.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Embassy: U.S. Report on Espionage Case Is </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- The allegations about the
so-called China's "theft" of nuclear weapons and missile secrets
are sheer fabrications out of ulterior political motives, the
Chinese Embassy in the United States said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is an attempt to stir up anti-China feelings and divert
people's attention," the embassy said in a press release. "We
firmly believe that the American public can make its judgement and
reach a fair conclusion."
</P>
<P>
A U.S. House special committee headed by Republican lawmaker
Chris Cox issued a 872-page report Tuesday, asserting that China
obtained secret information on seven nuclear warheads and the
neutron bomb in "two decades of espionage" at U.S. nuclear weapons
laboratories.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese embassy press release said China has all along
strictly abided by norms governing international relations in its
ties with other countries.
</P>
<P>
"China has developed a limited nuclear capability through
self-reliance. Our nuclear weapon systems are purely for defense
purpose," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
It said some people in the United States are clinging to Cold
War thinking and trying to derail China-U.S. relations by dreaming
up stories about China's spying. "Their attempts will not succeed
because what they are doing does not serve the interests of the
United States, nor is it in conformity with the common aspiration
of the Chinese and American peoples for friendly relations between
the two countries," the Chinese embassy said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Liu Xiaoming, minister of the Chinese Embassy in the
United States, said Tuesday that Cox's report is not new in
tracing China as an enemy.
</P>
<P>
The American public is for better relations with China, Liu
said in a CNN interview. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
