<HEADLINE> Britain Loses One Olympic Place in Equestrian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Britain's three-day eventing team
has lost the Olympic place it won at the World Equestrian Games
after a horse at the event was found to have broken drug rules.
</P>
<P>
Rider Polly Phillips and her mount Coral Cove were disqualified
from last October's games after the horse was found to have
breached prohibited substances regulations.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports on Tuesday, the Judicial Committee
of the International Equestrian Federation ruling has cost the
British team the bronze medal, and the Olympic place that went
with it.
</P>
<P>
The horse, which finished seventh individually, had higher than
permitted amounts of salicylic acid in its body.
</P>
<P>
The committee rejected evidence put forward by Ms Phillips
about the amount of the substance found in the horse.
</P>
<P>
But it did agree that there was no deliberate attempt by the
rider to affect her horse's performance.
</P>
<P>
Ms Phillips was given a mandatory disqualification, a one-month
suspension and ordered to pay 2,118 pounds towards costs.
</P>
<P>
The bronze medal has now been awarded to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Italy has taken the place at the Sydney 2000 Olympics lost by
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The British team still have a chance to qualify, at the
European Championships in Germany in September.
</P>
<P>
Ms Phillips has yet to decide whether to mount an appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
