<HEADLINE> U.S. Cox Committee Releases Anti-China Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 25 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Congress selected
committee released an anti-China report Tuesday, alleging that
China obtained nuclear secrets through "espionage" from the United
States. The U.S. allegation was entirely denied by China.
</P>
<P>
The 872-page report was drawn up by the Cox Committee, a
special House of Representatives committee headed by
Representative Christopher Cox.
</P>
<P>
The report, released after months of wrangling between the Cox
Committee, the White House and the intelligence agencies, asserted
that China got secret information on seven nuclear warheads and
the neutron bomb in "two decades of espionage" at U.S. nuclear
weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
In response to the U.S. allegation, Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao said in Beijing on Tuesday that the Cox
report was "merely a fallacy" dreamed up by a few people in the
United States with ulterior motives and in essence an attempt to
stir up anti-China feelings and divert people's attention.
</P>
<P>
Some Americans are sticking to the Cold War mentality and are
making a great effort to dream up stories about "China's spying"
on U.S. nuclear technology, Zhu said at a regular press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The attempt to stir up feelings about "China threat" and
anti-China sentiment is "doomed to fail", he said.
</P>
<P>
Cox, a Republican from California, claimed at a press
conference that the "illegally transmitted information" is useful
for the design and improvement of China's ballistic missiles,
but he said the report should not cast a shadow over China's
entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
"I personally think it is a useful thing for China to be
admitted to the WTO on commercially acceptable terms," Cox said.
</P>
<P>
Following the release of the Cox report, U.S. President Bill
Clinton said Tuesday that his administration will continue the
policy of engagement with China.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly believe that our continuing engagement with China
has produced benefits for our national security," Clinton said
</P>
<P>
Norm Dicks, a member of the Cox Committee, said that "the
Unites States still possesses overwhelming nuclear superiority
over China with more than 6,000 strategic nuclear warheads,
compared to China's total of about two dozen".
</P>
<P>
"China has for years had nuclear weapons capable of reaching
the United States, but China's nuclear force is retaliatory in
nature. The information obtained from the U.S. will not change
that character," he said.
</P>
<P>
China launched its own satellites and successfully tested its
atomic bomb years before it established diplomatic relations with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Dicks, a Democratic Representative, said the U.S. government
should continue its engagement policy towards China.
</P>
<P>
"I think it would be a mistake for us to change our basic
policy towards China, so I hope that we will still continue a
policy of engagement with our eyes open." Dicks said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said some Cold War-minded Americans try to
increase military spending by stiring up "China Threat".
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Senate Appropriations Subcommittee reportedly
boosted spending for security and intelligence by 53 million
dollars, a 40 percent increase.  
</P>
</TEXT>
