<HEADLINE> NATO Clears Revised Plan for Kosovo Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Decision-making body of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) on Tuesday approved a revised
plan for an expanded Kosovo ground troops to police law and order
after Serbs withdraw from the southern Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The NATO's North Atlantic Council will handed over the new plan
to NATO generals for final authorization. Under the plan, an
estimated 50,000-strong force will be sent into Kosovo from the
Republic of Macedonia once Serb forces withdraw from Kosovo on the
basis of a political agreement between the West and the Republic
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The forces will be mainly formed by European allies with a
sixth of the unit sent by the United States. The original plan,
drawn up last year, called for a NATO-led international force of
about 28,000 to implement a peace agreement between the Yugoslav
government and Kosovo's ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
But a NATO spokesman said that the force will have "very sharp
teeth as well as very big teeth if anybody should try to oppose it
carrying out its mandate or to threaten its personnel".
</P>
<P>
"I would imagine the bulk of the operational maneuver
battalions that would constitute the force would come from the
NATO countries," NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters at NATO
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The NATO military authorities are expected to assess the plan
and detail the force's needs before the end of the month, NATO
sources said.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana also said here today that
NATO is determined to stick to its strategy of air strikes against
Yugoslavia as the war entered its third month.
</P>
<P>
There had already been results, and progress towards a
political plan had been made in the past two months, the NATO
chief told a news conference after meeting with Spanish Prime
Minister Aanar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
