<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall Sharply Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell sharply
again on Tuesday as investors continued to be concerned with
higher interest rates despite sound economic reports.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 123.58 or 1.2
percent at 10.531.09. The index suffered a loss of 174.61 points
or 1.6 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two separate economic reports boosted the market briefly but
concerns about the interest rates among investors outweighted
optimism sparked by the reports, giving up all the gain of nearly
100 points in early session. The Conference Board reported that
consumer confidence rose nearly one-half a point in May while a
manufacturing group forecast stronger growth in the second half of
this year with little inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
In response to a 0.7 percent increase in consumer price, the
Federal Reserve decided a week ago to leave interest rates
unchanged but leaned to monetary tightening if more inflationary
pressures emerge in the coming months. The move pulled most
indexes down in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index fell 22.25 at 1,284.40 and the technology heavy Nasdaq
composite index fell 72.76 at 2,380.90.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 8.71 at 617.34 while the American Stock
Exchange index fell 6.57 at 778.84. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 5.94 at 434.45.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by 7-to-4 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,941 down, 1,089 up and 534
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 816.27 million shares from 734.99
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
