<HEADLINE> Demand for Smart Handheld Devices to Grow Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Unit shipments of smart
handheld devices are expected to reach total 8.9 million worldwide
this year, according to a forecast report released Tuesday by U.S.
research firm International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
This volume represents an increase of 34.5 percent over actual
1998 unit shipments of 6.6 million. By 2000, IDC expects growth to
increase to 44.5 percent as the industry continues to see strong
demand for devices pricing between 200 and 300 U.S. dollars, and
the emergence of new smart phones from major handset suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Listing as a key factor driving the accelerated growth for the
market, IDC said that there is a rising interest for deploying
smart handheld devices in the enterprise to meet the needs of
mobile workforce.
</P>
<P>
From a regional perspective, the United States accounts for 45
percent of worldwide shipments of the devices today. But IDC said
that Western Europe and Japan will quickly become stronger areas
of growth.
</P>
<P>
There is a need for a low-cost integrated wireless device and
value-added service that enables users to conduct voice calls,
send and receive short e-mails and access snippets of Internet
data, IDC said. Regions such as Western Europe and Japan are
poised to be the market leaders due to their wireless
infrastructure and propensity for adopting cellular technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
