<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone's Peace Talks Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 25 (Xinhua) -- The west African regional bloc ECOWAS
formally launched much-desired Sierra Leone peace talks Tuesday in
Lome, Togo's capital.
</P>
<P>
But representatives of the rebel Revolutionary United Front
(RUF) and the government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah were not
expected to start direct talks until Wednesday because of a delay
in agreeing procedures, according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The two sides went to the negotiation table under great
international pressure. The ECOWAS, the United Nations and the
United States had earlier jointly brokered the ceasefire to be
followed by the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The rebels argued that they should join an interim
power-sharing government, prior to holding general elections in
four year's time, and gaining some key posts in the government.
</P>
<P>
But President Kabbah, who was elected to office in 1996,
insisted that the rebels must transform themselves into a
separate political party first and then take part in the general
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
