<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Cancellation of Debts Owed by Poorest Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 25 (Xinhua) -- Italy is actively campaigning for the
complete cancellation of debts owed by the world's poorest
nations, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference here in celebration of the 36th
anniversary of the Organization of African Unity, Dini said that
Italy was working on a set of proposals to be presented to the
world's seven most industrialized nations when they meet in next
June.
</P>
<P>
"We are working on a project to identify the world's poorest
and most indebted nations, particularly in sub-Saharan regions,"
Dini said.
</P>
<P>
"We want their debts to be completely canceled, along with
those of a number of countries in central America," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that such a gesture by "more developed countries"
would be a unique sign of generosity and solidarity which would
"allow these countries to resume their development."
</P>
<P>
He also said that other developing nations which were less poor
but still struggling under the weight of massive debts should have
their burdens lightened.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Italy seized the initiative in this area by
announcing that it would be writing-off 1.56 billion U.S. dollars
in debts owed to it by the world's poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
Dini was optimistic that Italy's proposals would be well
received, saying that "there seems to be substantial agreement on
this position."
</P>
<P>
He also announced that Italy would work to ensure that greater
resources were put aside for boosting collaboration with
developing states and assisting their development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
