<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Youth Crime Rises in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN May 25 (Xinhua)--More German children and young people
were involved in crimes last year though the country's overall
crime rate declined, Bonn's Interior Ministry reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Totally 152,774 children aged under 14 were caught by police as
crime suspects in 1998, 6 per cent more than the number in 1997,
the ministry said in its annual crime survey.
</P>
<P>
Most of them were involved in shoplifting, it said.
</P>
<P>
And youths aged 14 to 18 were linked by police with crimes in
3.4 per cent more cases, with 5 per cent more young people aged 18
to 21 being suspected with criminal involvement.
</P>
<P>
Drug-related crimes in Germany also rose by 6 per cent, to
216,682 cases. The ministry attributed it to the rising use of
drugs such as cannabis.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Germany filed 6.5 cases of crimes in 1998, dropping 2
per cent from a year before, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
Cases of murder and manslaught dropped by almost 10 per cent in
1998, to 2,383, but the total number of violent crimes fell by
mere 0.1 per cent to 186,306.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry pointed out it was the first decrease in
violent crime in Germany since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The number of car thefts fell by over 18 per cent to 112,717
cases in 1998. The survey said this was partly due to improving
car anti-thefting technology.
</P>
<P>
More crimes were solved by German authorities last year, said
the survey, quoting that some 3.4 million cases were solved by
police, a rate of 52.3 per cent and 1.7 per cent higher than year
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
